<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-President Satisfied With Japan Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 24 (Xinhua)-- Visiting Chinese Vice-President Hu
Jintao told a press conference here Friday afternoon that he felt
satisfied with the result of his present Japan trip.
</P>
<P>
Hu said he had reached consensus on a series of major
issues with leaders of the Japanese government and political
parties, as well as people from various sectors.
</P>
<P>
Hu said the Chinese side holds that bilateral ties are
generally "satisfactory" while the two countries are constantly
expanding links in every field.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin's upcoming state visit to Japan
this fall will be a "historic one" and will bring Sino-Japanese
ties up to a new stage, he added.
</P>
<P>
He emphasized that in the current international situation,
Sino-Japanese relations are not only related to the fundamental
interests of the two peoples, but also to the peace, stability and
development in Asia and the world at large.
</P>
<P>
China and Japan should seize the opportunity, take lessons from
history and make joint efforts to establish the framework of
Sino-Japanese ties oriented towards the 21st century, Hu said,
adding that there is no obstacles on the Chinese part in promoting
bilateral good-neighborly and friendly relations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
