<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe University Students Clash with Police </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Running battles between students
of University of Zimbabwe (UZ) and heavily armed riot police
continued Friday at the campus, with the students trying to force
their way out into the Harare city center.
</P>
<P>
The students who gathered in groups said they had wished to
stage a peaceful demonstration into the capital in solidarity for
one student who was shot and seriously injured by a police
officer during a demonstration on Wednesday, the Zimbabwe News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
However, armed riot policemen sealed the troubled country's
highest institution of learning to prevent the students from
marching into the city.
</P>
<P>
Other armed riot police also surrounded Africa Unity Square in
the city center near the building of the Ministry of Higher
Education and Technology.
</P>
<P>
"We sense that the students might march into the city today
and there is a possibility of them being violent, that is why we
are here," said a police officer.
</P>
<P>
However, UZ vice-chancellor Graham Hill said the students were
just having skirmishes with the riot police and there were no new
developments yet from Thursday's situation.
</P>
<P>
The demonstrations started Wednesday after students objected
to the privatisation of all non-academic activities of the
institution, including the cafeteria system among other problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
