<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Major Chinese Trade Fair Getting More Overseas Visitors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A businessman from the
Neitherlands ordered several pieces of Chinese-made furniture
today at the 83rd Guangzhou Export Commodity Trade Fair and said
the prices and quality are acceptable, and that the only thing
Chinese exporters could do is increase competitive ability on the
international market by improving quality.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 50,000 other people from outside China have visited
China's oldest and largest export trade fair, that's 7 percent
more than for the last fair. This spring fair begins on April 15
and ends on May 30.
</P>
<P>
This shows that foreign businessmen are still interested in the
Chinese market in spite of the feared negative effects of the
financial turmoil in Asia, says Liu Xiangdong, Assistant minister
of Foreign Trade and Economic Cooperation. Southeast Asian
countries and the Republic of Korea have increased their viability
on the world market by devaluing their currencies, which has been
seen as a major challenge to Chinese exporters.
</P>
<P>
The number of visitors from these countries has decreased as
was expected, but what was unexpected is the fact that the number
of businessmen from European, American and African countries has
increased remarkably, according to a fair organizing committee
official.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
