<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Unveils New Economic Stimulus Package </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Japanese government unveiled
Friday a record 16.6 trillion yen (128 billion U.S. dollars)
economic stimulus package covering public works spending, tax
cuts, financial reforms, property market reforms and foreign
assistance to save the country from a recession.
</P>
<P>
"To overcome this severe economic condition and achieve a
strong economic recovery, we need to carry out drastic measures,"
the government said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The package, with 12.3 trillion yen (about 94.6 billion
dollars) in actual stimulus spending as its centerpiece, is the
largest-ever economic package worked out by the Japanese cabinet
in a bid to pull its economy back on track.
</P>
<P>
The steps were intended "to expand domestic demand, strongly
push economic structural reform and promote disposal of bad
debts," the government said.
</P>
<P>
The package includes four trillion yen (about 30.8 billion
dollars) in income tax cuts over two years and 7.7 trillion yen
(about 59.3 billion dollars) in public works spending.
</P>
<P>
Business leaders applauded the new economic package, but said
it will have at best a temporary impact on the economy as it does
not include permanent income tax cuts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
