<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Resignation of Nepali Cabinet Minister Accepted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Nepali King Birendra has
accepted the resignation of Khum Bahadur Khadka, minister for
forest and soil conservation and supplies on the recommendation of
Prime Minister Girija Prasad Koirala, said a notice issued Friday
by the King's Principal Press Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The notice said the minister resigned due to health reasons and
the prime minister himself has taken over the post. Now Koirala
holds concurrently five posts including that of defense, foreign
affairs and royal palace affairs.
</P>
<P>
It was learnt that Minister Khadka offered resignation
Thursday, two days after he was inducted into the cabinet, under
the pressure from some MPs of his own Nepali Congress (NC) party.
</P>
<P>
As Khadka was home minister under the governments led
respectively by Sher Bahadur Deuba and Surya Bahadur Thapa, he
should be logically responsible for the upsurge of corruption and
smuggling in the country.
</P>
<P>
Most of NC MPs boycotted parliament sessions for a second
straight day Thursday to show their displeasure at the induction
of tainted MPs into the cabinet, The Kathmandu Post said.
</P>
<P>
Minister of State for Industry and Labor Amar Raj Kaini and
Assistant Minister for Women and Social Welfare Kamala Panta, who
were picked up by Koirala on Tuesday in his expansion of the
cabinet, had refused to take the oath of office until Friday.
</P>
<P>
The present government is a minority government of the NC, the
largest party in parliament. Sources said the NC is now
negotiating with the Communist Party of Nepal (Marxism-Leninism,
CPN-ML) over the formation of a coalition government.
</P>
<P>
Before the formation of a minority government on April 15, the
NC tried to forge an alliance with the CPN-ML but failed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
