<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi FM on Relations with India </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Bangladeshi Foreign Minister Abdus
Samad Azad said Friday that India's new government has assured him
that India would honor the commitment made by the previous
government, the national news agency BSS reported.
</P>
<P>
Azad, who went to India as a special envoy of Bangladeshi Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina, made the remarks after returning from his
four-day "goodwill visit" to New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
He said that Indian prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee told
him that they would honor the water sharing treaty between the two
countries and go ahead with the decision agreed upon earlier to
hold regular meetings under the auspices of joint rivers
commission to resolve the problem of 54 common rivers.
</P>
<P>
India agreed to have all-round cooperation with Bangladesh and
showed keen interest to work to bridge the existing trade
imbalance, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it was emphasized at all meetings that there should be
regular exchange of visits by leaders of the two countries at high
level.
</P>
<P>
The present Indian government also wants to have all-round
relations with Bangladesh and offers to support the country in
different areas including science and technology, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the question of insurgency, Azad renewed Dhaka's stand to
New Delhi that the territory of Bangladesh would not be used
against any other country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
