<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Banning Direct Marketing Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- People involved in the direct
marketing scheme in the Chinese capital have responded calmly to
the State Council's ban on direct sales several days ago.
</P>
<P>
But some sellers gathered in twos and threes in front of the
direct marketing companies, apparently discussing the ban.
</P>
<P>
DishDrop Amway's Beijing Branch reported no returned products
and there wasn't even a drop in the number of buyers, most of whom
said they came to buy the products for their own use.
</P>
<P>
A person in charge of Amway Beijing said that Amway respects
the Chinese government's policy but would not withdraw from
China. But, he said, the company is considering readjusting its
business strategy by using sales methods that "fit in with Chinese
realities".
</P>
<P>
A Beijing commercial administration official said that big-name
direct marketing companies like Amway have business principles and
standard sales methods, but the problem is that some of its
agents' behavior is not that decent.
</P>
<P>
Because of the rampant cheating and swindling, the Chinese
government has made all sorts of direct marketing schemes illegal,
including licensed ones like Amway.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Administrative Bureau of Industry and Commerce
officials say they will close down illegal pyramid sales companies
and help those that have licenses to cope with the new conditions.
</P>
<P>
Even though Beijing has regulations on direct marketing, it is
difficult to supervise and there have been reports of misconduct
by sales agents, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing gave licenses to 24 companies in direct marketing last
year and has handled over 100 legal complaints, and handed out
860,000 yuan in fines. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
