<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kiriyenko Grateful to All Duma Deputies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Sergei Kiriyenko, who was just
approved by the Russian State Duma as prime minister on Friday,
expressed thanks to the deputies who took part in the third vote.
</P>
<P>
He was equally respectful and grateful to the deputies who
voted either "yes" or "no", who took and did not take vote papers,
the Itar-Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko asked the deputies to forget in their future work the
emotions that preceded the confirmation vote in the lower house of
parliament.
</P>
<P>
He noted that his candidacy's approval indicated that "neither
we nor you need great upheavals, that both we and you need a great
Russia".
</P>
<P>
He said that his administration will work hard to win the
confidence of the State Duma and all citizens of Russia.
</P>
<P>
President Boris Yeltsin is "pleased" with the results of the
voting, said Alexander Kotenkov, the president's representative in
the Duma.
</P>
<P>
After the endorsement of Kiriyenko as prime minister, Acting
First Vice Prime Minister Boris Nemtsov told reporters that the
approval enabled a normal work of the government, and there was
also a whole possibility to form a new cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Communist Party Leader Gennady Zyuganov, who firmly rejected
the president's nominee, said the third voting was "unfair." It
was the continuation of the old policy, he added.
</P>
<P>
In his opinion, it should have been an open vote so that
everyone's stand would be clear and visible.
</P>
<P>
Leader of the Our Home is Russia movement, Russian ex-premier
Viktor Chernomyrdin welcomed the decision. He said now Russia has
both the government and the State Duma, which is a very positive
factor for the country.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin threw the government and parliament into disarray on
March 23 when he fired the entire cabinet, headed by long-time
Prime Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin. Yeltsin accused the government
of failing to improve the economy and people's living conditions.
</P>
<P>
He then nominated Kiriyenko, a former banker and energy
minister, as prime minister. He said that he was the right man for
the job and will breathe new life into economic reforms.
</P>
<P>
But the deputies in Duma rejected Kiriyenko twice in the past
two weeks by solid margins.
</P>
<P>
In his turn, Yeltsin threatened to disband the State Duma, if
the nomination was not approved in the third voting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
