<HEADLINE> Kinkel Asks Arafat Not to Declare Palestinian State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel
on Friday called on visiting Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat not
to declare a Palestinian state in 1999 in a bid to prevent the
Middle East situation from worsening.
</P>
<P>
"The unilateral declaration of a Palestinian state could make
things more critical," said Kinkel at a news conference here after
talks with Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, however, said that he still intended to go ahead with
the plan which he said was justified by the 1994 Oslo peace accord
with Israel, an agreement that paved ways for further talks to
secure the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"We must announce that a state will be created and that its
capital will be East Jerusalem," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu of
failing to live up to his commitments under the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
Asked if he will meet with Netanyahu in London next month when
the two leaders are to hold separate talks with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, Arafat said he still had to see what
kind of offers Albright will put on table.
</P>
<P>
The United States is reportedly pressing for a further Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
Israel had opposed a 13 percent withdrawal from the occupied
land proposed by Washington, saying that it would just return less
than 10 percent land to Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
During his talks with Kinkel, Arafat also called on Europe to
make more peace efforts in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
In response, Kinkel said Europe would seek to strengthen
cooperations with the U.S. to revive the stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Arafat is also due to meet German Chancellor Helmut Kohl later
this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, King Hussein of Jordan is also in Bonn on Friday for
separate talks with German President Roman Herzog, Kohl and Kinkel.
</P>
<P>
Both Middle East leaders will attend a ceremony this evening in
the southern city of Baden-Baden where King Hussein will be
honored with the 1998 German media prize for his contributions to
the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
