<HEADLINE> Candidates for HK Legislature Election Hit Record Number </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- There are a total of 167
candidates for the first Legislative Council election of the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR), hitting the record
number over the previous legislature elections.
</P>
<P>
This was announced by a spokesman for the Constitutional
Affairs Bureau at a press conference here shortly after a two-week
long candidates nomination for the May legislature election ended
Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
According to the final results released by the Registration
Electoral Office, the total number of nomination papers received
totals 120, involving 167 candidates after deducting seven
withdrawals and one invalid nomination.
</P>
<P>
Of the total candidates, 81 come from the geographical
constituencies, 61 from the functional constituencies, and 25 from
the Election Committee.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said he was pleased with the record number of
candidates.
</P>
<P>
"It is particularly encouraging that 81 candidates from 34
lists will contest in the geographical elections," he said.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the candidates come from all walks of the
community, the spokesman said: "we welcome this. It gives voters
more choice. It also underscores widespread support for the
election."
</P>
<P>
He said that the Electoral Affairs Commission is finalizing the
necessary practical arrangements for the election.
</P>
<P>
"We are confident that the election will be conducted in an
open and fair manner, and the legislature so returned will be
credible and representative," the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The government will also step up publicity in the next few
weeks in accordance with the publicity plan to urge all eligible
voters to cast their votes on May 24, he added.
</P>
<P>
At Friday's press conference, the spokesman, in a reply to
questions on the qualification to be nominated as a candidate for
the Legislative Council election, repeatedly stressed that as
stipulated clearly in the Legislative Council Ordinance, except
for the 12 designated functional constituencies, a candidate must
be a Chinese citizen who is a permanent resident of Hong Kong with
no right of abode in any foreign country.
</P>
<P>
In the case of a candidate who has the right of abode in a
foreign country, this would require the completion of the process
of his giving up the right of abode of that country before the
close of nomination, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Legislative Council election will produce all the 60
members with 20 to be returned from geographical constituencies
through direct election, 30 from functional constituencies and 10
from an 800-strong Election Committee. 
</P>
</TEXT>
