<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Clears Final Hurdle in Germany </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The upper house of the German
parliament Friday followed a similar move at the lower house a day
earlier by giving overwhelming support for the single European
currency euro, clearing the way for Germany to join the euro's
launch in January, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The ambitious currency integration project of the European
Union was approved almost unanimously by the Bundesrat, which
represents Germany's 16 federal states, with the only abstention
coming from the eastern German state of Saxony.
</P>
<P>
On Thursday, the parliament's lower house, the Bundestag, also
gave the green light to the euro project with a vote of 575 to 35.
</P>
<P>
The parliament's votes mean that Germany will be able to join
ten other EU states to start the new currency on January 1, 1999,
if their membership could be formally confirmed at a EU summit
meeting in Brussels early May.
</P>
<P>
Despite the broad political support, opinion polls show that
between 50 to 70 percent of the German public are still dismayed
about abandoning their rock-hard German mark in favor of the still
untested euro.
</P>
<P>
Created exactly 50 years ago, the mark has been cherished by
Germans as the symbol for the country's economic miracle in the
post-war era and a safeguard against skyrocketing inflations that
robbed their savings early this century.
</P>
<P>
German government officials, however, pledge that the euro is
set to be as stable as the mark.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
