<HEADLINE> U.S. Trade Representative Welcomes China's Tariff Cuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Trade Representative
Cherelene Barshefsky said at a press conference here this evening
that she welcomes China's new tariff-cut proposals.
</P>
<P>
The proposals China put forward at the seventh session
of the World Trade Organization China Working Group Meeting
at Geneva enearly April are "helpful", she said.
</P>
<P>
She also spoke about the "broad, in-depth and very
constructive" talks she had with Minister of Foreign Trade and
Economic Cooperation Shi Guangsheng and State Councilor Wu Yi,
saying they have put negotiation back on track.
</P>
<P>
The meetings are designed to make progress on the WTO
negotiations as directed by U.S. President Bill Clinton and
Chinese President Jiang Zemin when the two leaders met in
Vancouver last November.
</P>
<P>
Those discussions included industrial and agricultural tariffs;
non-tariff measures, like quotas and licences; professional
services like accounting and legal services; wholesale and retail
distribution; telecommunications; and banking, securities, and
insurance.
</P>
<P>
Acceptance in the WTO is a very complex process, she said, but
added that she is quite pleased with the overall tone and
seriousness displayed by her Chinese colleagues.
</P>
<P>
The discussions were "quite in-depth" and they were meant to
determine how best to proceed with negotiations, she said.
</P>
<P>
Her discussion with senior Chinese officials covered
agriculture, intellectual property rights, and the recent ban on
direct sales.
</P>
<P>
She said that her agriculture negotiator will be coming here in
about two weeks to discuss a range of issues on WTO accession and
on a series of bilateral disputes.
</P>
<P>
She said the piracy situation in China has "dramatically
reversed" in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
She disclosed the next round of bilateral intellectual property
rights consultation may be held in early June in Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
