<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Has Highest Rates of Child Asthma </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Britain has the worst record for
childhood asthma in the world, with more than one million children
suffering from the condition, according to an international study
published Friday.
</P>
<P>
The International Study of Asthma and Allergies in Childhood,
which was carried out in 56 countries and involved 463,801
children aged 13 and 14, found that only Ireland, Australia and
New Zealand have proportionately as many young sufferers as
Britain.
</P>
<P>
They are followed by North, Central and South America. But
eastern European countries, Indonesia, Greece, China, Uzbekistan,
India and Ethiopia have the lowest prevalence of the condition
among children of the same age group.
</P>
<P>
In Britain, as many as three million people suffer from the
disease, which causes some 2,000 deaths each year.
</P>
<P>
The study showed enormous variations in the incidence of the
breathing disease, with some places having 60 times the levels of
others.
</P>
<P>
It said that environmental factors were critical to the
development of childhood asthma, and dust mites, which live in
pillows and mattresses, are mostly blamed for triggering asthma
attacks in childhood.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
