<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK Flights Delays Remain at Record High </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The number of UK scheduled flights
which were delayed for more than 15 minutes over the last quarter
of 1997 remained at record high, according to figures offered by
the Civil Aviation Authority (CAA) Friday.
</P>
<P>
The CAA said that only 73 percent of flights had arrived or
taken off on time during the period of time, the same as over the
previous quarter of 1997 and the lowest since 1992 when the
statistics were first compiled.
</P>
<P>
The figures were drawn from a study of the country's 10 major
airports, including Heathrow, Gatwick, Stansted, Luton,
Manchester, Birmingham and Edinburgh.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the delays were caused by passengers not turning up,
passengers checking in bags and then going missing and a variety
of technical problems, such as aircraft being taken out of
service," said a CAA spokesman.
</P>
<P>
He added that delays due to air traffic control problems only
stood at nine percent.
</P>
<P>
"Air traffic is rising and therefore so are the delays. The
more flights you have, the more flights will be delayed," he
explained.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the London Heathrow airport also had a
record high number of flights which were delayed, with only 69
percent of its flights arriving or taking off on time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0037 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
