<P>
NAIROBI, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The ten Red Cross workers
kidnapped by Somali gunmen on April 15 were set free Friday
morning and arrived at Nairobi in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Some of them burst into tears when embraced tightly by their
family members who had been waiting for them at the Wilson
Airport for about one hour.
</P>
<P>
The workers, one of whom a French woman, were abducted by
nearly 40 armed militiamen nine days ago when they landed at a
small airstrip near north Mogadishu. However, they looked fit
and in good health.
</P>
<P>
Among the hostages are two pilots from Kenya and South Africa
respectively, an American, a French, a Norwegian, a Belgian, two
Swiss doctors, a German and a Somali from the Somali Red Crescent
Society.
</P>
<P>
"Most of them (the kidnappers) were polite," the 47-year-old
Swiss said. He has worked for the International Committee of Red
Cross (ICRC) for ten years.
</P>
<P>
"We've been treated as hostages, been treated as people in
detention. We were confined to a sitting room... We had access
to food, water, sanitary facilities, and apart from a few tense
moments, generally-speaking, we were treated well," he told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
"Hope was always there... We all had a lot of faith in our
Somali colleagues who actually from the very first day we knew
</P>
<P>
... tried to find means to release us from the situation," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, he noted that their release was a result of the
joint and massive efforts by "all major players in Somalia" and
the ICRC and thus could not be contributed to a single major
political figure.
</P>
<P>
"The release of the hostages has been obtained
unconditionally; no ransom has been paid," said the Geneva-based
International Committee of Red Cross in a press release Friday.
</P>
<P>
But sources close to the kidnappers and negotiators indicated
to Xinhua correspondent in Mogadishu that 60,000 US Dollars was
given to the abductors Thursday night and 40,000 Dollars was
given to them Friday morning. The money reportedly came from
local Somalis.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers were once reported to have demanded a
one-million-U.S.-Dollar ransom. But ICRC regional office in
Nairobi claimed it has never been approached by any faction over
demands.
</P>
<P>
The kidnappers are said to be loyal to a renegade member of
northern Mogadishu's military leader Ali Mahdi's Hawiye clan but
not under the direct control of Mahdi.
</P>
<P>
Mahdi and some other major leaders in Somalia expressed their
"strong regrets" about the abduction immediately after the
hostages were released.
</P>
<P>
"This has been an isolated incident and it is not representing
the Somalis in general," said Mahdi, who called on the ICRC and
other aid agencies to resume operations in the country as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
Since the abduction happened, the Somali capital saw the
withdrawal of all relief agencies and expatriate staff. About 45
percent of the city's population is dependent on relief services.
</P>
<P>
So far the ICRC has not yet discussed when to resume their
operations in Somalia.
</P>
<P>
The hostages were first moved around 8:25 a.m. Friday morning
from their place of captivity to the ICRC run hospital of
Keysaney, about a mile north of the capital, where they were
offered medical checkup and refreshment drinks and food and
talked with their families by phone. 
</P>
</TEXT>
