<HEADLINE> Mowlam Urges N.Irish Voters to Give Peace Chance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- As the vital referendum for
Northern Ireland peace deal is approaching, British Northern
Ireland Secretary Mo Mowlam on Friday urged voters in the province
to give a historic opportunity to discard old hatreds.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to a group of young people, Mowlam said in Belfast
that "young people have a chance to vote for a more peaceful
future."
</P>
<P>
Northern Ireland and the neighboring Irish republic will hold
referendums on the historic peace agreement to a conflict that has
cost more than 3,200 lives in 30 years.
</P>
<P>
"I haven't worked for the last 12 months to find an agreement
for them to vote 'no' and go back to the old days. I am also very
clear that it's their decision and their choice. No-one will tell
young people how to vote -- they will make their own minds up,"
said Mowlam, a chief negotiator in the tough talks that achieved
the peace deal two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Gerry Adams, leader of Irish Republic Army's
political wing Sinn Fein, said on Friday he will have a further
round of talks with Prime Minister Tony Blair in London on Monday.
</P>
<P>
He told reporters he will also meet Jim Steinberg, U.S. deputy
national security adviser, who visits Belfast on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein did not sign the Northern Ireland peace deal, but
political analysts expect the party to back the accord at a
special congress to be held on May 10.  
</P>
</TEXT>
