<HEADLINE> Intra-Afghan Dialogue Likely to Be Delayed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Uncertainty shrouds the much-
trumpeted and first-ever talks between the Afghan Islamic Taliban
militia and their rival Northern Alliance as a senior U.N.
official and Afghan sources Friday hinted a delay in the dialogue
scheduled for Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Meeting of the two-member joint Coordination Committee could
not be held here on Friday, which was supposed to discuss
modalities for the Steering Committee's meeting, reported the New
Network International (NNI) Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Taliban delegation, which was due in Islamabad Friday, has
not arrived in the Pakistani capital so far and this would delay
the scheduled talks Saturday, NNI quoted a U.N. official as
saying.
</P>
<P>
"We are getting close to open the talks but just need to get
the Taliban here," said the official in the Islamabad-based U.N.
Afghan peace mission.
</P>
<P>
Afghan sources said Friday evening that members of the Taliban
delegation, who had been waiting in Kabul for several days to fly
to Islamabad, have now gone to Kandahar, a big city in southern
Afghanistan, for consultations with Taliban's central leadership.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Taliban Friday reiterated their stance that the
main item on the Saturday's meeting with the Northern Alliance
should be the formation of Ulema (religious scholar) Commission,
according to the NNI.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to the acting Head of the U.N. Special Mission
for Afghanistan, N. Gobi, the Taliban said that the Steering
Committee should discuss four issues including members of the
Ulema Commission, their qualification, authority and guarantee
from all sides for the implementation of its decisions.
</P>
<P>
However, the Northern Alliance has emphasized that the meeting
should also deliberate on a ceasefire, exchange of prisoners and
removal of blockade of humanitarian aid to Afghanistan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
