<HEADLINE>   Over 100 Kilograms of Heroin Seized in Turkey </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- A total of 125 kilograms of
smuggled heroin were seized in Turkey on Friday and four suspects
were arrested, the semi-official Anatolia News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The heroin, worthing about 9 million U.S. dollars was found by
Turkish police and gendarme during two separate anti-drug
operations in the country's western province of Edirne and eastern
province of Van neighboring Iran.
</P>
<P>
The agency said that acting on a tip off, the police discovered
30 kilograms of heroin when they stopped a car at Kapikule Border
Gate in Edirne.
</P>
<P>
The heroin, packaged in 13 parcels and hidden in the ceiling of
the car was about to be delivered to Hamburg, Germany, the agency
said, adding that one person in connection with the drug smuggling
has been arrested.
</P>
<P>
In another separate anti-drug operation in Ortayol village of
Baskale town in Van province, Turkish gendarme soldiers tracked
down and seized 95 kilograms of heroin valued at 8 million
dollars. Three people were detained during the operation.
</P>
<P>
The agency said the heroin was brought from Iran through
mountains and would have been marketed after being processed in
the Ortayol village.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Iran are on the transit route of drug trafficking to
Europe from the border areas of Afghanistan and Pakistan. In 1996,
Turkish police seized 4.4 tonnes of heroin, which accounted for 40
percent of the world's total haul. 
</P>
</TEXT>
