<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe International Trade Fair Opened </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian president Benjamin
Mkapa called on African countries to unite for the promotion and
defense of their commercial interests when he officially opened a
three-day Zimbabwe International Trade Fair in the country's
second largest city of Bulawayo this afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Mkapa said African countries needed to stand together to
promote and defend their interests in the emerging liberalised
world trade regime, the Zimbabwe News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
"In this new economic liberation war our weapons are maximum
collective self-reliance and regional economic integration which
begins at the bilateral level and proceed to the strengthening of
southern African countries," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the private sector was the vanguard in this endeavour,
while the government would provide the rear base by creating the
requisite enabling environment.
</P>
<P>
The president also urged developed countries to assist poor
countries to weather the negative impact of the new world trade
regime.
</P>
<P>
"Appropriate compensatory measures and facilities, including
tariff reduction and a system of preference, must be diligently
and urgently implemented," he said.
</P>
<P>
As far as Africa was concerned, he said, concerted efforts
needed to be made to increase its share of international trade,
which fell from 3.1 percent in 1990 to a mere 2.1 percent by the
year 1995, translating into a loss of 200 billion U.S. Dollars in
potential export earnings over a period of five years.
</P>
<P>
He added the industrial development strategy of the Southern
African Development Community (SADC) had outlined the way
forward, by gearing, among other things, towards reducing
dependence on imported manufactured goods from outside the region
from 46 percent to 35 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
"At the same time it seeks to increase intra-regional trade
from five percent to 12 percent of the total trade by the year
2000," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 35 countries including the U.S. Germany, China,
Argentina, Singapore, Indonesia and Syria attended the fair and
are exhibiting their products. 
</P>
</TEXT>
