<HEADLINE> Remnant UNITA Militiamen Attack U.N. Office </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Remnant militiamen of the
National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) have
been attacking various areas in the central part of the country
in the past few days.
</P>
<P>
Early Thursday morning, dozens of UNITA soldiers launched an
armed attack at Ngove Town in the southeast of Huambo Province,
looting everything from the local office of the United Nations
observer mission along with properties of the local residents,
before retreating to the forests bordering with Huila Province,
local media Friday quoted police sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to Diogo Joao, head of the local police, some
residents died while others sustained wounds during the attack.
However, he didn't reveal the casualties.
</P>
<P>
In Benguela Province in the central coastal region, UNITA
forces reportedly ambushed a fully-loaded bus on Wednesday
evening, killing one passenger, and wounding seven. One other
passenger was kidnapped.
</P>
<P>
Local police said this was the fourth ambush to vehicles in
the area.
</P>
<P>
Reports said due to the insecurity caused by the UNITA forces,
residents in Benguela Province were seriously worried. Up to
26,000 refugees have gathered in Ganda city in the central part
of the province.
</P>
<P>
Dumilde Rangel, governor of the province, revealed that by now
nine regions in the province are still under UNITA's control.
Local government is making great efforts in safeguarding people's
life in the province.
</P>
<P>
Huambo, Benguela and Huila provinces in central Angola have
become a "dangerous triangle area" threatened by the UNITA
forces. The national police and U.N. soldiers in Angola have
enforced armed patrol in the region so as to prevent further
sabotage from the former rebel movement. Endiem

