<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Parliament Apologizes for Guernica Bombing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Following a similar move made by
German President Roman Herzog last year, the German parliament
Bundestag Friday also formally apologized for the German air raid
of the northern Spanish town of Guernica during the Spanish Civil
War 61 years ago.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimously adopted declaration on Friday, the Bundestag
expressed its support for the apology made by Herzog last April on
occasion of the 60th anniversary of the attack.
</P>
<P>
The Bundestag also said the apology made by the German
president and shared by the German parliament should serve to
improve the foundations for a peaceful and friendly future between
the German and Spanish peoples.
</P>
<P>
On April 26, 1937, during the Spanish Civil War, German Nazis
sent bombers of the "Legion Condor" squadron to attack Guernica in
assistance of the troops of Francisco Franco against those of the
Republicans. The war ended in 1939 with Franco becoming dictator
of Spain.
</P>
<P>
The attack reduced around three-quarters of the defenceless
Basque town to debris. The death toll has never been established,
with estimates ranging from 300 to 1,500.
</P>
<P>
Herzog's apology, which read "I want to face up to the past and
explicitly acknowledge the guilty part played by German aviators",
represents Germany's first official admission of responsibility
for the bombing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0049 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
