<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Reported to Link redeployment With </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Israel is to propose to link
the further Israeli troop pullout with the final-status talks
during the forthcoming visit by U.S. special peace envoy Dennis
Ross, Israel Radio reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
Zalman Shoval, the former Israeli Ambassador to the U.S. and
currently head of the World Likud Organization, told Israel Radio
that Israel's response to the U.S. proposal on the second pullback
must be based on Palestine's readiness to enter accelerated
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
According to the accords between the Israelis and the
Palestinians, they should settle the thorniest issues of
Jerusalem, final borders and Palestinian refugees in the
final-status talks.
</P>
<P>
Shoval is Netanyahu's close friend and is reported to be
reappointed Ambassador to the U.S..
</P>
<P>
In his speech Friday, he urged Washington to explain to the
Palestinians that "if we approach the fast track in negotiations
on permanent status, then the exact percentage of the
second-phase redeployment may look like less important and less
crucial than it is today."
</P>
<P>
Ross is due in Jerusalem Saturday, together with U.S. Assistant
Secretary of State and former U.S. Ambassador to Israel Martin
Indyk, to begin a new round of mediation aimed at reviving the
Israeli-Palestinian talks.
</P>
<P>
The talks was installed in March last year when Israel began
construction of the Jewish housing project on Har Homa in East
Jerusalem, which the Palestinians wants as the capital of their
would-be state.
</P>
<P>
A meeting has been scheduled between Ross and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on Saturday night. Ross is also then
to hold talks with Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Top on Ross' agenda is to solve the dispute over the size of
Israel's second-phase troop withdrawal, thus setting the stage for
the planned four-way talks in London to be co-hosted next month by
British Prime Minister Tony Blair and U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Ross will demand that Israel accept the U.S. proposal for troop
withdrawal from a further 13.1 percent from the West Bank over 12
weeks, with each step met by Palestinian security gesture.
</P>
<P>
Although Netanyahu has till now refused to accept any pullback
more than 9 percent, some reports said he is drafting a map on a
11 percent redeployment.
</P>
<P>
By agreeing to increase the extent of the second pullback,
Netanyahu may hope to pressure the Palestinian National Authority
to start immediately the final-status talks of Jerusalem, which
are long overdue.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu has made it clear that, after carrying out the
first two phases of the further redeployment, he would integrate
the third pullback into the final-status talks. He is fully
aware of the strong opposition to another redeployment by the
right-wingers who are dominating his government.
</P>
<P>
In proposing for accelerated permanent talks, Netanyahu also
apparently hoped to conclude a package deal in favor of
Israel by negotiating from an advantageous position when Israel
is still controlling large area of the Palestinian territories.
</P>
<P>
But this has been rejected by the Palestinian side which
demands for the accurate implementation of the signed
agreements.
</P>
<P>
Israel should have finished troop withdrawal in three stages by
this summer under the Hebron accord signed in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Frustrated over the lack of progress in the peace process,
Arafat and PNA officials have recently repeatedly announced their
determination to declare an independent Palestinian state in May
next year, regardless of achieving a peace treaty with Israel
or not. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0051 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ambassador Shen: China Is in favor of UN Chief's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Shen said assistance to Africa contributes to world development
and prosperity and is in the common interest of the international
community as a whole. It is by no means one way charity to Africa.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said international assistance should proceed
from the actual conditions in Africa and truly benefit the
African people, without attaching any conditions.
</P>
<P>
Shen said African countries are the masters of Africa. They
know best their problems and needs. Only they can decide upon
their course of development in light of their specific
conditions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
