<HEADLINE> German Bank Predicts Euro to Start at 1.95 German Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, April 24 (Xinhua) -- One of Germany's largest commercial
banks, the Dresdner Bank, Friday predicted that the planned single
European currency euro is likely to be launched at an exchange
rate of 1.95 German mark in 1999 and will remain strong against
the U.S. dollar at least for the next five years.
</P>
<P>
According to Dresdner Bank's estimates, EU countries currently
have a world market share of about 20 percent compared with some
16 percent for the United States. However, only about 31 percent
of world trade are currently executed in EU currencies compared
with 48 percent in the dollar.
</P>
<P>
With the European currency integration, the demand for the euro
would rise automatically, experts of the bank said, adding that
especially petroleum-exporting countries would have a strong
interest in making the switch from the dollar to the euro.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the bank was also upbeat about the euro's outlook to
rival the dollar as an international reserve currency.  
</P>
</TEXT>
