<HEADLINE> S. Africa Pledges to Help Mozambique to Remove </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 24 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will continue
helping Mozambique to rid itself of anti-personnel landmines
planted during the liberation wars in that country, South African
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Landmines were a significant impediment to socio-economic
reconstruction and development in Mozambique. "South Africa
therefore views demining to be fundamentally a humanitarian task
of the highest priority and importance," Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks at the presentation of a
certificate to his Mozambican counterpart Leonardo Simao to
verify the successful completion of the demining of Maputo
Province by South African experts.
</P>
<P>
He also handed certificates to 10 Mozambicans who have been
trained in demining techniques over the past two months.
</P>
<P>
More than 5,000 landmines were destroyed, clearing 163
hectares of land and unlocking the agricultural potential of the
Currumane Dam region.
</P>
<P>
South Africa was to send a specialist to help Mozambique
continue its own mine-clearing operations.
</P>
<P>
Nzo repeated earlier calls on all African states to ratify and
put into effect the Ottawa Convention which prohibits the use,
production, transfer and stockpiling of anti-personnel landmines.
</P>
<P>
The time had arrived to stop making political statements on
the dimensions of the landmine problem, Nzo said.
</P>
<P>
"We now seek the active and sustainable involvement of the
international community towards the total eradication of this
silent killer from the soil of our continent," Nzo added.
</P>
</TEXT>
