<HEADLINE> Tanzania Vows to Combat Child Labor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Tanzanian government
will take part in a worldwide campaign against child labor,
Minister of Education and Culture Juma Kapuya has said.
</P>
<P>
While inspecting an anti-child labor march here Friday, the
minister said that he is worried about the child labor situation
in Tanzania which has become worse since 1980s.
</P>
<P>
Plagued by poverty, many children in Tanzania are subjected to
becoming street vendors and work in difficult environment like
sisal, tea, cotton, sugar estates and mines which are hazardous
to their health and are exposed to nasty behaviors like taking
drugs and prostitution.
</P>
<P>
The minister has expressed fears that children were among the
more than 90 victims who were buried alive two weeks ago in mine
pits in Meremani in the northern region of Arusha.
</P>
<P>
Although child labor has been widely criticized in Tanzania, a
number of small-scale miners prefer to employ children. Teenage
boys who are more flexible and efficient in passing complicated
narrow passages in mines pits are nicknamed "snake boys."
</P>
<P>
Kapuya also appealed to international agencies dealing with
children's rights to provide financial aid to the educational
development in developing countries so that more children can
receive education since it is one of their basic rights.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of residents and students have participated in the
march Friday, led by international activities who are touring the
African continent campaigning against child labor.
</P>
<P>
It is reported that marches against child labor are also
taking place in other continents, such as Asia and Latin America.
Statistics indicate that more than 250 million children worldwide
are subjected to child labor.
</P>
<P>
Kapuya also urged parents, the community and children
themselves to participate in the war against child labor.
</P>
<P>
Speak at the function, the International Labor Organization
(ILO) resident representative, Christine Bockstal, said that
child labor is a blatant human right abuse and therefore should
be fought by concerted efforts of governments, Non-Government
Organizations (NGOs), research institutions, international
agencies and individuals.
</P>
<P>
Bockstal said that child labor in many parts of the world has
been greatly reduced except in Africa.
</P>
<P>
The march will head to the Arusha Region Saturday, organizers
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
