<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-24 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey to Launch New Diplomatic Drive on Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Deputy Prime Minister
Bulent Ecevit said Friday that Ankara would launch a new
diplomatic drive on Cyprus by explaining the island's historical
realities to young foreign diplomats.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks after meeting with Turkish Cypriot leader
Rauf Denktash, who arrived here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ecevit said that "the circumstances that created the Cyprus
problem and the developments before and after the (1974 Turkish)
intervention on the island will be explained to young foreign
diplomats, who do not know the realities or pretend not to".
</P>
<P>
Referring to the European Union's (EU) decision to start
accession talks with Cyprus, Ecevit said that has made solution of
a bi-communal, bi-zonal federation unrealistic, adding that "the
Turkish state on Cyprus is an undeniable reality".
</P>
<P>
Recently, the United States has stepped up efforts to find a
solution to the Cyprus issue.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Special Presidential Envoy for Cyprus Richard Holbrooke
will visit the island in May in a bid to bring the parties
together and outline a framework for an ultimate settlement.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus has been divided into the Greek Cypriot-dominated south
and Turkish Cypriot-controlled north since 1974 when Turkish
troops landed and took over the northern third of the island in
the wake of an abortive coup by Greek Cypriots seeking union with
Greece.
</P>
<P>
Turkish Cypriots unilaterally declared a "Turkish Republic of
Northern Cyprus" in 1983, which is only recognized by Turkey.
</P>
</TEXT>
