<HEADLINE> U.S. Hopes for Resolution of Helms-Burton Law Dispute </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union's decision
to drop a World Trade Organization (WTO) complaint against the
U.S. over an anti-Cuba U.S. law may improve chances for a possible
agreement in the controversy, the State Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the fact that the decision was made not to go
forward with a case before the WTO indicates desire on the
Europeans' part to come to a solution," said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"But the next step is to see whether we can come to an
understanding that no country should want to see expropriated
property benefit the expropriator," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law was enacted in 1996 after two small U.S.
planes was shot down by the Cuban military when they flew into
Cuba's skies.
</P>
<P>
The law punishes foreign companys which uses confiscated U.S.
properties in Cuba. The EU insists it violates the free trade
principles and filed a complaint before the WTO in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
