<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Homeless Become Victims in Illegal Asbestos Removal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The homeless are increasingly
becoming victims in illegal asbestos removal scams where they are
employed without training or adequate protection, the U.S. Justice
Department said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The department announced indictments against three Wisconsin
men, who are accused of bringing workers from a Chattanooga,
Tennessee, homeless shelter to their state to illegally remove
asbestos from a building being demolished.
</P>
<P>
Attorney General Janet Reno called such activity "a shameful
human exploitation" and promised the government would take every
step to prosecute illegal asbestos removal cases that involve
untrained homeless people, teen-agers and unqualified day
laborers.
</P>
<P>
"Knowingly removing asbestos improperly is criminal," Reno told
a news conference also attended by Environmental Protection Agency
(EPA) Administrator Carol Browner. Using vulnerable people for
such activity violates "the basic standard of human decency."
</P>
<P>
Asbestos fiber, often used to insulate older buildings, is a
hazardous material whose fibers can become deeply imbedded in the
lungs and cause respiratory illnesses and even cancer. Its removal
is regulated closely and workers must follow special removal
procedures.
</P>
<P>
The department cited prosecutions in nine states since
September involving the hiring of untrained workers, often
homeless people or unwary teen-agers, to rip out asbestos. They
included.
</P>
<P>
Reno said these cases are "the tip of the iceberg" since
violations often are not reported.
</P>
<P>
The department sent warning notices to homeless shelters and
announced a telephone hotline for people to call if they believe
someone is being hired for improper asbestos removal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
