<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees Urges Support </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Security Council of
the United Nations should create a stand-by international force in
support of humanitarian operations in Africa, Sadako Ogata, United
Nations high commissioner for refugees, said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the council's open debate on the U.N. chief's
report on Africa, Ogata said the mixed nature of groups hosted in
refugee camps -- refugees coexisting with fighters, criminals and
genocidaires -- has been the greatest challenge to the work of her
office throughout the Great Lakes crisis.
</P>
<P>
Ogata said the trend will expand further if no measures to deal
with mixed groups in a rapid and effective manner are designed and
implemented soon.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner said maintaining the civilian nature of
refugee camps is the responsibility of host governments. However,
different situations may require a variety of responses. There are
situations in which building or supporting local capacity are
inadequate to maintain the civilian character of camps.
</P>
<P>
She said separation of refugees from criminals can then become
an important security requirement, and there may be no other
option but to deploy international police or military forces.
</P>
<P>
Ogata expressed her strong support for the secretary-general's
call for the creation of an international mechanism to assist host
governments in maintaining the civilian nature of camps.
</P>
<P>
The commissioner hoped that the Security Council will give
concrete follow-up to this recommendation and will examine the
possibility to create a stand-by international force in support of
humanitarian operations.
</P>
<P>
Ogata said her office stands ready to help develop procedures
and techniques for police and military forces to carry out this
type of activity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
