<HEADLINE> Albright's Trip Not Designed to Achieve Particular </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright's upcoming trip to China was designed to lay
the groundwork for the Sino-U.S. summit in Beijing rather than to
achieve particular negotiating outcome, a State Department
spokesman said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
James Rubin told a press briefing that Albright would "prepare
the way and arrange for many of the details" of the summit meeting
scheduled for late June.
</P>
<P>
"This travel of the secretary of state to countries of this
kind is not designed to achieve a particular negotiating outcome
the way, say, a meeting of the Contact Group or some pre-prepared
negotiation would," said the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
Albright will start her four-nation Asia trip Monday, which
will take her to Japan, China, South Korea and Mongolia. She will
stay in Beijing Wednesday and Thursday. This is the first of her
four planned visits to the region this year.
</P>
<P>
The secretary of state will meet with Vice Premier Qian Qichen
and Foreign Minister Tang Jiaxuan in the Chinese capital on the
summit-related issues.
</P>
<P>
"What is important, however, is laying the groundwork for the
president's trip to China, trying to advance our agenda in terms
of getting concrete progress in human rights, in stopping the
proliferation of weapons of mass destruction, as well as seeing
whether there's an opportunity to move China forward on its
application or attempt to join the WTO, the World Trade
Organization," Rubin added.
</P>
<P>
Washington has come to realize the importance of conducting
"strategic dialogue" with China on a number of issues instead of
pursuing a China policy of "containment." It stated repeatedly
that progress has been made on human rights and non-proliferation
through negotiations, but a lot of work still lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
Rubin said that the U.S. officials will try to make progress on
the three specific areas of concern. He did not elaborate if an
agreement could be expected on China's admission to the WTO before
or during President Bill Clinton's trip to China.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky is now in Beijing
to assess the possibility. She told reporters in the Chinese
capital Friday that the negotiations had picked up momentum but
China could expect no favorable treatment in its accession to the
WTO.
</P>
<P>
"I am quite pleased with the overall tone and seriousness
displayed by my Chinese colleagues and we have reestablished
momentum," she said after two days of negotiations, adding she
still has some concerns.
</P>
<P>
China asks to be allowed in as a developing country but the
U.S. and some other industrialized countries oppose.
</P>
<P>
Albright will make stopover in London on her way back home on
May 4 to meet separately with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in an effort to
break the stalemate on the Middle East peace process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
