<HEADLINE> OAU Calls for Support for Africa's Own Efforts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of
African Unity (OAU) has called on the international community to
"be more human rather than statistical" in dealing with the
continent.
</P>
<P>
This was expressed here Friday by Machivenyika Maparanga,
permanent representative to the U.N. of Zimbabwe, the current
OAU chairman.
</P>
<P>
He told the U.N. Security Council's debate on Secretary-General
Kofi Annan's report on Africa that the international community
should go beyond facts and figures but see the true scene of
Africa.
</P>
<P>
News of economic growth has been communicated to the
international community mainly in terms of statistical figures
such as percentage growth of the gross domestic product, reduced
budget deficits, curtailed public spending and lower inflation
rates, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, some of African countries were actually
de-industrializing, and were no nearer to eradicating absolute
poverty among the majority of its people.
</P>
<P>
Many African countries continue to spend more on debt-servicing
than they did on education or health, or on education and health
combined in some cases, he added.
</P>
<P>
He appealed to the international community to assist Africa by
recognizing its need for accelerated human resource training,
technology transfer, debt remission, capital investment and
access to international markets on the basis of equitable terms
of trade. 
</P>
</TEXT>
