<HEADLINE> U.S. Sees Little Prospect of Breakthrough in London Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. State Department
Friday warned against any optimism on breakthrough in peace talks
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright will hold on May 4 in London
with Israeli and Palestinian leaders.
</P>
<P>
"I think it's very hard to be optimistic and hopeful about the
Middle East peace process after a series of meetings in which
Secretary Albright and Ambassador (Dennis) Ross have used all the
ingenuity they can muster to try to find creative solution to
these problems," State Department spokesman James Rubin told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
Rubin made the remarks as Ross and Assistant Secretary of State
Martin Indyk left for the Middle East to prepare for the London
meetings between Albright and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu and Between Albright and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Rubin described the peace process as "increasingly moribund"
and the obstacles to progress remained serious because of
reluctance of the Middle East leaders to compromise during the
past nine months of U.S. mediation efforts.
</P>
<P>
"We have no reason at this point to know that this meeting will
yield anything but the kind of refusal to make hard decisions that
we've seen in the past," he said.
</P>
<P>
Albright and other U.S. officials have repeatedly warned that
the United States might stop its mediation efforts if there seems
to be no prospect of a breakthrough. But a senior State Department
official said a failure in London would not necessarily mean the
end of the road, and that a judgment "will depend on where we
think we are." 
</P>
