<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French Gaullist Leader Not to Seek Succession </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippe Seguin, president of
France's Gaullist movement, the Rally for the Republic (RPR), said
Saturday that he might not seek succession in the first election
of PRP presidency.
</P>
<P>
The election, by universal vote of party members, is to be
held in January 1999.
</P>
<P>
"The reasons for me not to be the candidate are getting the
upper hand in my head," the 54-year-old RPR leader told a meeting
of his party militants in Paris.
</P>
<P>
Seguin took over the post at the demand of President Jacques
Chirac from former Prime Minister Alain Juppe after the right-wing
parties were routed by the Socialist-led left-wing coalition in
the legislative elections one year ago.
</P>
<P>
"I have an awareness of being ... one of the major obstacles to
the implementation of the strategy (of renewing the RPR)," he
said.
</P>
<P>
As one step in the remoulding of France's mainstream
right-wing, the RPR is breaking with its ally, the centrist Union
for French Democracy (UDF), after some key UDF leaders allied
with the extreme-right National Front in the regional elections
last month.
</P>
<P>
If Seguin steps down, Nicolas Sarkozy, a rising star in the
RPR, is most likely to be the next Gaullist leader of
France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0089 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 15:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saddam Blasts U.S. for Prolonging Sanctions on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi President Saddam Hussein
has held the U.S. responsible for prolonging the U.N. sanctions on
Iraq, accusing Washington for fabricating lies in this regard.
</P>
<P>
In a letter sent to Third International Conference on the
embargo imposed on Iraq, which is being held in the Greek capital
Athens, Saddam said the Iraqi people have been able to uncover
such U.S. lies.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has accused the United States of using the U.N. weapons
inspectors to make reports that Iraq has not done enough to
eliminate its banned weapons as required as a precondition to lift
the eight-year-old U.N. sanctions.
</P>
<P>
"Many world advocates of justice have become fully aware of
the facts and that only the remaining imperialists and enemies of
freedom, justice and peace support the United States in adopting a
stance of hostility," said the president in the letter which was
carried by the Iraqi News Agency Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He expressed his confidence that Iraqis will achieve their
ultimate goals with the great support from the international
community.
</P>
<P>
As to the international meeting, the Iraqi president said that
"the conference is an interpretation of world organizations and
figures' conscience that reject tyranny and hegemony and calls for
just peace."
</P>
<P>
Saddam expressed his high appreciation of the participants'
concern about the suffering undergone by Iraqis who suffered a lot
in the U.N. sanctions imposed after the Iraqi of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Caledonia Independence Party Adopts Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The New Caledonian independence
party, the Front of Kanak Socialist National Liberation (FLNKS),
authorized its leaders to sign an agreement with the French
government over the territory's independence, on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The agreement delays a referendum on independence for the
French overseas territory in the South Pacific for 15 to 20 years.
</P>
<P>
It promises full autonomy for local government and more power
to the Kanak community prior to a possible full independence by
2013 at the earliest, or 2018 at the latest.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was clinched Tuesday by the FLNKS, the pro-France
party of the Rally for Caledonia in the Republic (RPCR) and the
French government.
</P>
<P>
Six-hundred FLNKS representatives in a closed-door congress in
Poindimie, north of the island, authorized party leaders to sign
the agreement with French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin, and the
RPCR, on May 5 in Noumea, capital of the territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
