<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African-Caribbean Pacific States to Meet in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- African-Caribbean Pacific
Countries (ACP) will meet in Barbados next month to adopt a
common position on new Lome conventions which they will present
to the European Union in September, a Zimbabwean minister has
said.
</P>
<P>
Industry and Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira said the ACP
countries would meet for four days from May 1 to 4 to draft a
position paper for their discussions with the European Union for
the renewal of the Lome conventions, the Zimbabwe News Agency
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The minister said in an interview that the negotiations on new
conventions would last for one to one and a half years.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Barbados meeting would review three main
areas, namely, non-reciprocal trade under which goods from ACP
countries enter Europe duty free, the!European investment fund
and assistance to the poorest countries.
</P>
<P>
"We hope to keep the non-reciprocal facility because it is
important to us. In the case of Zimbabwe, if we were to pay duty
for our horticultural and clothing products it would make them
less competitive," he said.
</P>
<P>
The Lome conventions, in place since 1975, have been the basic
framework for trade, development and aid cooperation between the
71 ACP countries and 15 EU countries.
</P>
<P>
They will come to an end in February 2000 with the expiry of
the Lome IV convention.
</P>
<P>
ACP heads of state and government met in Gabon last year and
endorsed a framework for serious negotiations with the EU while
the latter has come up with a "green paper" which forms the basis
upon which debate on the future of the conventions beyond 2000
can proceed.
</P>
<P>
However, fundamental political and economic changes have so
far taken place, developments that make the future of EU-ACP
relations uncertain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Set to Formulate New Law on Higher Education (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Many experts pointed out that Chinese colleges and universities
have lost their initiative due to rigid administration by the
Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang University President Pan Yunhe said "China's existing
system of higher education fails to meet the requirements of
modern times."
</P>
<P>
The draft stipulates that higher education of China should be
put under the overall leadership of the State Council, but the
powers of local governments in the management of higher education
should be expanded.
</P>
<P>
Currently, some of the colleges and universities in China are
run by the Education Ministry and some others by local governments or
other ministries.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, a few private institutions of higher education
have also been established in the country.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources indicate that lawmakers will engage in
enthusiastic discussions regarding regulations on the
self-decision power of universities, their management system and
investments from governments at various levels.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese legislature passed the Law on Education in 1995,
and the nation's 2,170 colleges and universities now have a
total enrollment of 5.67 million students. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Services Return to Normal in Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Sri Lanka's postal services are
gradually returning to normal with the announcement of the
Essential Service Regulations, according to postal department
sources here Saturday evening.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan government has declared posts and
telecommunications essential service last night in a bid to end a
prolonged overtime boycott by postal workers who have launched a
44-day long postal strike which has severely affected the
country's economy and administration.
</P>
<P>
The postal employees have been urged to fulfill their duties
and the government has decided to take stern action against those
employees who were directly or indirectly involved in the
disruption of postal services, the official radio said this
evening.
</P>
<P>
Issuing a special announcement, Post Master General Soma
Kotakadeniya said that leave for all employees in the postal
department will be canceled until further notice.
</P>
<P>
However, employees who obtained leave for medical reasons
should submit a government medical certificate, the radio added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
