<HEADLINE> Yi Jingqian Struggles to ITF Women's Circuit Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Yi Jingqian exploited her home
advantage to enter the final of the '98 ITF women's circuit
Saturday, edging her Japanese rival Morigami Akiko in straight
sets 6-2, 7-4.
</P>
<P>
Cheered on by a crowd at the Guan Lanhu club tennis center, Yi,
224th on the world rankings, finished the first set easily with
6-2.
</P>
<P>
Yi led the second set with 4-0 before an error made by the
referee in the fifth game to give her a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
Unexpectly, the misjudge did a magical effect to swift the loud
cheers from Yi to the enraging Akiko each time as she rallied back
to 6-5.
</P>
<P>
When Yi tied Akiko at 6-6, the home fans again turned cheers to
Yi's side until she finally won the tiebreaker 7-4.
</P>
<P>
"We were breathless with tension to watch Yi's tough fight. She
is great!" The crowd sighed with emotion after the match.
</P>
<P>
In another semi-final, third seed Kim Eun-ha of South Korea
ousted second seed Shaughnessy Meghann of the United States 6-4,
6-4 to earn a showdown against Yi Jingqian.
</P>
<P>
The mixed pair Gail Biggs from Australia and Hotta Tomoe from
Japan romped second seed Japanese duo Asagoe Shinobu and Obata
Saori 6-2, 6-3 in the doubles semi-final.
</P>
<P>
Biggs and Tomoe will meet another mixed pair Australian Barclay
Catherine and South Korean Kim Eun-ha in the final. 
</P>
</TEXT>
