<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Killed in S. African Road Accident </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen people were killed
and eight others were injured in a horrible accident near Cape
Town Saturday, South African Press Association (SAPA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The accident, involving a minibus taxi and two cars, occurred
shortly before 7 a.m. (0500 GMT).
</P>
<P>
Fifteen of the victims, 11 women and 4 men, were burnt to
death when the taxi burst into flames on impact, trapping the
occupants inside the vehicle, SAPA said.
</P>
<P>
An occupant of a Mercedes-Benz was killed and another occupant
was injured. All five occupants of the other cars were injured.
</P>
<P>
Cape Town's mayor Theresa Solomon visited the scene but was
too overcome with grief to comment.
</P>
<P>
Minibus taxis, which usually transport black people, are
considered dangerous by South African road users. They may stop
at virtually any time and anywhere to pick up passengers and a
large proportion of their drivers do not have legal driving
licenses.
</P>
<P>
Sixteen people died when two minibus taxis collided at an
intersection near Khayelitsha, about 35 kilometers from Cape Town
last Sunday. It was reported that one of the minibuses failed to
stop at the intersection before the red light. 
</P>
</TEXT>
