<HEADLINE> Moya Beats Krajicek for Monte Carlo Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Spain's Carlos Moya rallied from
2-4 down in the third set to oust seventh seed Richard Krajicek
4-6, 6-1, 6-4 Saturday, entering the final of the 2.2 million
U.S. dollars Monte Carlo Open.
</P>
<P>
Moya, 1997 Australian Open finalist, raced all around the clay
court retrieving balls and neutralised the effect of the 13 aces
which Krajicek powered down during the one-hour 53-minute contest.
</P>
<P>
The 21-year-old Moya improved his 1998 record to 17 wins, eight
defeats as he beat Krajicek for the second time in two years at
Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
Krajicek was competing in his first event since the birth of
his daughter Emma on March 26.
</P>
<P>
Moya will await the winner from Saturday's second semi-final
between Frenchman Cedric Pioline and Spanird Alberto Berasategui.
</P>
