<HEADLINE> Jordanian Families to Visit Relatives in Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A group of 26 Jordanian
families will arrive in Kuwait on May 4 for a three-day stay to
visit their relatives jailed in the Gulf state, a Kuwaiti official
announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Hamed Al-Refaei, head of the
International Organization Liaison Department said that the group
of 41 people will visit 25 Jordanian prisoners who have been
sentenced to imprisonment in Kuwait Central Prison for either
financial, criminal or security offenses.
</P>
<P>
He said the visit will be arranged by the International
Committee of the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait is keen to fulfill commitment to all international
human rights agreements, charters and declarations with an aim to
support international relations and strengthen cooperation among
international organizations, Al-Refaei said.
</P>
<P>
This will be the fourth visit to be made by theses relatives
since 1995.
</P>
<P>
The first two visits took place in June and September in 1995
and the last in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
Relations between Kuwait and Jordan had been strained
following the Gulf War in 1991 during which Jordan sided with Iraq
which occupied Kuwait for seven months before the U.S.-led allied
forces drove the occupation troops out.
</P>
<P>
But bilateral ties have been improving since last year within
the framework of a reconciliatory process by the Kuwaiti
authorities with the "former enemy states." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
