<HEADLINE> China Set to Formulate New Higher Education Law (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China's legislature is set to
deliberate a new law governing higher education in order to
standardize the management of Chinese colleges and universities.
</P>
<P>
The agenda for the Second Meeting of the Standing Committee of
the National People's Congress (NPC), scheduled to begin tomorrow,
calls for legislators to deliberate the draft Law on Higher
Education.
</P>
<P>
Chinese lawmakers are expected to be engaged in heated
discussions of the draft law, which outlines perspectives for
reforms of the nation's system of higher education, according to
reliable sources.
</P>
<P>
The NPC Legislative Affairs Commission organized in-depth
discussions between NPC deputies and well-known educationists
prior to the law's submission to the nation's most authoritative
law-making body.
</P>
<P>
The educational system reform centers on the management of
higher education, which is in urgent need of new policies,
according to Lanzhou University President Li Fashen.
</P>
<P>
Education reform will flounder if the Ministry of Education
controls the management system like "a bird in a cage," said Lu
Qiang, a professor at Qinghua University and an academician with
the Chinese Academy of Sciences.
</P>
<P>
"Each university should be entitled to enroll new students,
provide training and grant diplomas," said Lu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India to Have More Financial Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Indian Finance Secretary Montel
Singh Ahluwalia said Saturday that the government was
contemplating more reforms in the banking sector on the basis of a
report prepared by the Narasimham Committee on the financial
sector.
</P>
<P>
Inaugurating a "Banking Technology Concept Center" in Bangalore
city, capital of Karnataka state in southern India, he said that
more changes were likely as the government took a view of the
report.
</P>
<P>
The Narasimham Committee, formed by the former United Front
government with former governor of the Reserve Bank of India M.
Narasimham as its head to study financial reforms in the country,
submitted its report to Finance Minister Yashwant Sinha on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The committee favored the merger of strong public sector banks
and closure of weak ones where rehabilitation was not possible. It
opposed to the merger of strong banks with the weak on the grounds
that such a move would have a negative impact on the asset quality
of the stronger bank because of the "contaminated portfolio" of
the weak bank.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, a working group of the Reserve Bank of India
has suggested freedom to banks and development financial
institutions to explore gainful mergers.
</P>
<P>
The seven-member group, which submitted a report to Governor
Bimal Jalan of the Reserve Bank of India Friday, recommended a
super regulator to supervise and coordinate activities of multiple
regulators in the banking sector to ensure uniformity in the
country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
