<HEADLINE> Afghan Taliban Delegation Arrives for Talks with Rivals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The stage has been set for the
long-awaited intra-Afghan talks as the delegation of Afghanistan's
Islamic Taliban arrived here Saturday, one day late than the
schedule.
</P>
<P>
The four-member Taliban delegation, who was greeted by U.N.
officials at the Islamabad airport upon their arrival Saturday
afternoon, made no comment to reporters. The fifth Taliban
delegate has already been here.
</P>
<P>
Earlier in the day, a spokesman for the Pakistani Foreign
Office announced that the Joint Steering Committee, which is made
up of five delegates from the Taliban and nine from their rival
Northern Alliance, will meet here Sunday morning under the
auspices of the United Nations and the Organization of the Islamic
Conference (OIC).
</P>
<P>
The first face-to-face encounter between the two sides was
scheduled to take place from Saturday morning. However, it became
impossible as the Taliban delegation did not reach Islamabad until
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
Though the agenda of the forthcoming intra-Afghan talks has not
been known so far, it is believed the Taliban, who control two
thirds of Afghanistan, and the Northern Alliance, who controls the
remaining one third, will focus on the formation of the Ulema
(religious scholar) Commission, ceasefire and exchange of
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
OIC Assistant Secretary General Ibrahim Saleh Bakar, who
arrived here Friday morning, will jointly preside over Sunday's
meeting with N. Gobi, acting head of the U.N. Afghan peace mission
based in Islamabad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
