<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Welcomes Swiss Release of Mossad's Agent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Israel expressed on Saturday
its welcome to the release by Switzerland of its Mossad agent,
saying such a move could further enhance the friendly relations
between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio quoted Israeli government officials as saying
that Mossad's new director Ephraim Halevy has contributed a
lot for the release of its agent in Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
Five agents of Mossad, Israel's state intelligence and
spy organization, took part in a telephone bugging operation in
Switzerland in February this year and all of them were caught
red-handed by the Swiss police. The Swiss police let four of them
leave the country, but kept one agent for trial due to the failed
operation.
</P>
<P>
Swiss authority announced in Berne Saturday that the Mossad
agent was released on a heavy bail, but did not give the exact
sum paid by Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Swiss authority also said the agent was allowed to return
to Israel, but he would return to Switzerland when asked to stand
further trial.
</P>
<P>
The Mossad's failed operation in Switzerland was the second in
recent months following its failed assassination attempt on Hamas
(Islamic Resistance Movement) leader Khaled Masha'al last
September in Amman. The failed operations forced former
Mossad chief Danny Yatom to resign.
</P>
<P>
Halevy was appointed the new Mossad head on March 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
