<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Strengthen Protection of Land Resources </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A senior Land Administration
official said today that China plans to adopt strict land-use
regulations to protect its land resources.
</P>
<P>
"An amendment to the Land-Use Law scheduled for deliberation
tomorrow during the Second meeting of the National People's
Congress Standing Committee defines social interests as the top
priority for the use of land," according to Gan Zangchun,
department director of the State Land and Natural Resources
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
"The amendment will play a decisive role in protecting land
resources," said Gan at a one-day seminar sponsonered by the
Chinese Association for International Understanding and the Japan
Academy of Land Law.
</P>
<P>
Gan, who is also in charge of drafting the amendment, said the
Land-Use Law, the first land-use law since 1986, failed to meet
the needs for enforcing land management and providing practical
protection for arable lands due to the transformation of both the
economic system and economic growth mode, as well as China's
accelerated industrialization and urbanization.
</P>
<P>
The draft amendment will ensure an increase of arable land, and
the scale of land earmarked for construction should be fully
considered in the nation's overall planning, said Gan.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the draft includes measures for protecting
farmland, an approval system for requisitioning arable lands and
penalties for related violations.
</P>
<P>
Informed sources indicate that the draft is the latest step the
Chinese government has adopted to show its determination to
effectively protect land resources.
</P>
<P>
The one-year moratorium on the use of arable land for
non-agricultural purposes introduced last April effectively curbed
the trend towards land abuse and paved the way for establishing a
dynamic equilibrium for arable land.
</P>
<P>
Gan told Xinhua that China's land sectors are prepared to
cooperate with foreign counterparts to advance related domestic
legislations.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the pending commercialization of housing in China
will proceed in line with the Land-Use Law and will promote the
rational use of land resources.
</P>
<P>
Liang Xiangyang, general manager of the Beijing Eastern Huarui
Real Estate Consulting Co. Ltd. said the Land-Use Law and Law on
Real Estate will continue to guide development of the real estate
industry. He added that the draft will ensure better protection
for rational land use.
</P>
<P>
Liang expressed hope that regulations related to the real
estate industry, including housing prices, will be clearly
stipulated in order to promote the sound and timely development of
the industry. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
