<HEADLINE> Major News Items in Leading U.S. Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The following are major news
items in leading U.S. newspapers on Saturday:
</P>
<P>
The Washington Post:
</P>
<P>
-- President Boris Yeltsin prevailed over his opponents in
the lower house of the Russian parliament and won confirmation
as prime minister of Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
-- The sudden burst of airline alliances has concerned
government officials who said that the proposed deals may
warrant a broad look at whether the airline plans would violate
anti-trust laws or result in unfair competition.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times:
</P>
<P>
-- Reacting to warnings that heavy fighting in Yugoslavia was
on the verge of spilling over into Albania, U.S. administration
officials said the United States would seek a freeze on Yugoslav
assets held overseas and a stiffer ban on trade with the
Belgrade government as punishment for the bloodshed in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
-- A standoff between the United States and Russia apparently
derailed plans for a Security Council debate next week on
changing the emphasis of the Iraqi nuclear inspection process
from active disarmament to a long-term monitoring system.
</P>
