<HEADLINE> U.S. Replica Ocean-going Ship Visits Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Pride of Baltimore II, a
replica of American commercial ship Topsail Schooner Circa 1812,
arrived here on Friday for a week-long visit on its first Asian
Tour.
</P>
<P>
As a goodwill ambassador for the State of Maryland, Baltimore
and the Port of Baltimore, the ship had started "The Asia with
Pride Tour" last December from Baltimore's famous Inner Harbor.
</P>
<P>
After a four-month-long voyage, the ship arrived in Shanghai on
April 1, which was the first port of call on the tour. It later
visited Xiamen at China's southeastern coast, before arriving in
Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Baltimore Pride II and its 12-member crew will also visit such
Chinese ports like Guangzhou in South China and Kaohsiung and
Keelung in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
After calls to South Korean and Japanese ports, the ship will
return to Baltimore around the end of November this year.
</P>
<P>
Among the destinations on the Tour schedule are corporate
headquarters of three of Baltimore's largest customers -- the
China Ocean Shipping Company in Shanghai, Evergreen Marine in
Kaohsiung and Toyota Motor Corporation in Nagoya, Japan.
</P>
<P>
"Asia, which economy is developing so fast, is an important
part of the world," said Captain Jan Miles.
</P>
<P>
And he was obviously impressed by the amount of fishing ships
when Baltimore Pride II approached Shanghai in East China. "It is
really amazing to see so many Chinese ships around you," he said.
</P>
<P>
The 30-meter-long vehicle also features an instructional
program and a teacher aboard, Leslie Anne Bridgett, who is funded
through a federal "Christa McAuliffe" scholarship program and
selected through a statewide contest. She is sending back to
schools, via satellite and the Internet, log, pictures and stories
about life aboard Pride II and her adventures in the ports of call
on the tour.
</P>
<P>
"It is a once-in-a-life chance. And I really enjoy the voyage
and being part of it," she said. Five of the crew members are
female. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
