<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0132 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Combats Youth Crime: HK Security Secretary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Peter Lai, secretary for
security of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region, said here
Saturday that combating youth crime is one of the government's
priority tasks.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the "Right Decisions
Program" organized by the Hong Kong Junior Chamber, Lai noted that
in coping with the problem of youth crime, a three-pronged
approach including prevention, enforcement and rehabilitation has
been adopted over the years.
</P>
<P>
In 1995, an Action Plan to Tackle the Problem of Juvenile Crime
was announced, which has put forward a number of specific measures
to meet the objective of "prevention is better than cure," Lai
said.
</P>
<P>
One of the main initiatives of the Action Plan was the
establishment of a Student Discipline Team devoted to the
provision of professional support to schools on matters relating
to student discipline.
</P>
<P>
In the 1997/98 academic year, the team provided professional
advice to about 150 primary and secondary schools on how to deal
with "problem students."
</P>
<P>
At the same time, training courses on the same subject were
organized for about 400 discipline teachers of primary and
secondary schools in Hong Kong, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
In order to reintegrate young offenders into the community,
cautioned young offenders are referred by the police to
non-governmental organizations under the Community Support Service
Scheme for followup.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, publicity efforts have been strengthened by making
"Fight Youth Crime" the theme of the Fight Crime Publicity
Campaigns in the past three years, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that compared with 1995, the total number of
young offenders in 1996 dropped by 8 percent, from which there was
a further decrease of 11.1 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The downward trend continued in 1998, with the total figure for
the first two months dropping by 12.5 percent when compared with
the corresponding period in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"This persisting downward trend shows that the measures
mentioned above are effective in fighting youth crime," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
"However, there is no room for complacency and we are committed
to further improving our existing services. In this connection,
the Research on the Effectiveness of Rehabilitation Programs for
Young Offenders was completed recently," Lai said.
</P>
<P>
As recommended by the research, the Correctional Services
Department (CSD) has set up a new Rehabilitation Division in
January to ensure better coordination of its rehabilitation
programs and aftercare services, Lai said.
</P>
<P>
The CSD and Social Services Department (SWD) have widened the
spectrum of practical subjects for inmates to include computer
studies and language courses, he said.
</P>
<P>
The CSD has also increased the group counseling sessions
conducted by aftercare staff in half-way houses from five to eight
per week, Lai added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
