<HEADLINE> Nomination for HK's Legislative Election Successful: Local papers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong newspapers issued
editorials here Saturday, describing as a complete success the
nomination of candidates for the first Legislative Council
election in the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR).
</P>
<P>
The two-week-long nomination ended Friday with a total of 166
candidates nominated for the May 24 election, after deducting
seven withdrawals and two invalid nominations.
</P>
<P>
A commentary by Ta Kung Pao said the number of candidates for
the coming legislative election has exceeded those for the
previous Legislative Council elections before Hong Kong returned
to China last July.
</P>
<P>
This fully shows the local people's greater political
enthusiasm under the principles of "one country, two systems" and
"Hong Kong people governing Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
The paper noted that continued efforts should be made to imbue
the 2.8 million registered voters throughout Hong Kong with the
same political zeal so as to ensure that the election will be
conducted in a fair and civilized manner.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Wen Wei Po noted in an editorial that the record
number of candidates for the first Legislative Council election of
the HKSAR indicates that the Hong Kong people have really become
their own masters after Hong Kong's return to the motherland and
their consciousness about their civic duties and participation has
been greatly raised.
</P>
<P>
It also offers the registered voters more choices during the
election and helps implement the principle of balanced
participation, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
The paper pointed out that the 166 candidates come from various
sectors and strata of society in Hong Kong, thus laying the
foundation for the implementation of the principle of balanced
participation in the election which is an embodiment of the
democratic spirit and conforms to the actual situation in Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
The interests and demands of every sector and stratum of
society in Hong Kong should be fully reflected in the Legislative
Council. Only by doing so, can Hong Kong's social stability and
economic prosperity be maintained, the paper added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
