<HEADLINE> Rehabilitation Facilities Benefit Disabled in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The rehabilitation facilities
put in use in Hong Kong over the past year have benefited more
than 10,000 disabled people directly or indirectly, Andrew K. P.
Leung, director of social welfare of Hong Kong, said here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the beginning of this year, the HK government launched and
funded a medical service to provide treatment to disabled people
at home and it is now considering expanding this service, Leung
told the opening ceremony of a new rehabilitation facility.
</P>
<P>
Also, Leung said, a government-funded community-level network
of three rehabilitation centers has offered assistance to people
with chronic diseases, helping them re-enter the society and
prevent the relapse of their problems.
</P>
<P>
Leung said the Department of Social Welfare is now reviewing
its practice in the past year to draw experience for the future.
</P>
