<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HKSAR Government Puts Priority on Legislative Polls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- David Lan, secretary for home
affairs, said here Saturday that the government of the Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) is placing priority on the
May Legislative Council election.
</P>
<P>
"We are attaching importance to it because this presents us
with the first opportunity to select our first legislature to show
that Hong Kong people are quite capable of ruling themselves as
promised in the Basic Law," Lan said at a press conference here.
"The eyes of the world media would be focused on us."
</P>
<P>
He reminded registered voters that they have not only a civic
responsibility to cast their sacred ballots, but that they should
also realize that their participation would affect the development
of the political process in the future.
</P>
<P>
Lan expressed the belief that the electoral arrangement is
fair, open and honest and it should culminate in the election of a
credible and representative legislature, provided the electorate
gives it the full support it deserves.
</P>
<P>
Announcing details of an election publicity program, Shelley
Lau, director of home affairs, promised an all-out joint effort
with local organizations to carry the election message practically
to the doorsteps of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
All promotional tactics proven to be effective are being
resorted to, she said. They include roving exhibitions, special
programs and regular announcements on the radio and TV, posters,
pamphlets, advertisements, briefings for various groups,
audio-visual presentations, parades and carnivals, appeal messages
from well-known personalities, a wide range of useful souvenirs
and speeches by senior administration officials.
</P>
<P>
On Saturday morning, Justice Woo Kwok-hing, chairman of the
Electoral Affairs Commission, briefed candidates on the guidelines
for election-related activities at the Hong Kong Convention and
Exhibition Center.
</P>
<P>
Later, a meeting was held between Returning Officers and
candidates to draw lots to determine the order of names on the
ballot paper and to allocate designated spots for the display of
election advertisements.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest official figures, there are now a total
of 166 candidates running for the 60-seat Legislative Council on
May 24 after deducting seven withdrawals and two invalid
nominations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
