<HEADLINE> HKUST Drive Raises Public Awareness of Environment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, April 25 (Xinhua) -- An Environmental Protection Day
organized by the Hong Kong University of Science and Technology
(HKUST) on Saturday called on the public to pay more attention to
environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the campaign, Robert Law,
director of the Environmental Protection Department of Hong Kong,
said it is important for the public and the community to know and
understand environmental issues although the government has to
play a big role on such issues.
</P>
<P>
He described the HKUST effort as "valuable, saying such
activities will make it easier to solve the existing environmental
problems.
</P>
<P>
An official of the Agriculture and Fisheries Department also
urged public support and awareness on environmental issues. The
rich technological resources in Hong Kong's institutions of higher
learning should contribute to the protection of the environment,
he said.
</P>
<P>
This is the second Environmental Protection Day organized by
the HKUST following a successful campaign on the same day in 1997.
Several hundred people, including the university's faculty members
and students, high-school students and some tourists, joined the
event.
</P>
<P>
Activities of the day included seminars on red tide and the El
Nino phenomenon, a workshop for paper recycling, tree planting and
beaches cleanup. An activity coordinator said the campaign focuses
on education concerning environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
This year participants paid particular attention to red tide,
which has caused millions of HK dollars in losses to the fishing
industry and other sectors in Hong Kong.  
</P>
</TEXT>
