<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigeria Dismisses Western Sanction Threat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Nigeria will not be deterred by
any sanctions from the West, according to Minister of State for
Foreign Affairs Alhaji Buhari Baba.
</P>
<P>
The minister made the remarks Friday following the threat of
further sanctions by Britain and the United States after the
country's political parties nominated the head of state General
Sani Abacha as their consensus candidate for the August 1
presidential election.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria will continue to move on despite the threat, because
"this is not the first time we have been sanctioned, yet there
are functional projects in place," he said, quoted by the
Guardian Saturday.
</P>
<P>
He also accused Britain and the U.S. of "trying to undermine
the transition to civil rule program."
</P>
<P>
They don't recognize the sovereignty of Nigeria as a country
that has total control of its internal affairs, according to the
minister.
</P>
<P>
All the five registered parties in Nigeria last week adopted
Abacha as their sole presidential candidate. The development was
alleged by Britain and the U.S. to be a result of government
manipulation of the transition program.
</P>
<P>
However, Baba argued that all had been done under the guidance
of laws and in line with the established procedure and the
democratic process.
</P>
<P>
"So it is not enough excuse for the U.S. or Britain to impose
any sanction on Nigeria or to interfere in Nigeria's internal
affairs," said Baba.
</P>
<P>
"They have done that (sanction) before, yet we have continued
to survive it. There are several road construction projects, we
have medicines in hospitals and our educational institutions are
functioning. So even if they impose sanctions, I don't see that
posing any problem to us," he added.
</P>
<P>
He also accused the European Parliament of funding
pro-democracy groups in the country to "sabotage the transition
program". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
