<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Citizens Demonstrate Charitable Nature </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- On weekend mornings, middle
school students wearing ribbons printed with words "Messengers of
Charity in Guangzhou" can be seen walking urban streets to raise
money for charitable purposes.
</P>
<P>
They usually stick badges with the sign of a heart on the
clothing of those who donate money.
</P>
<P>
The charity program, launched two years ago, has attracted an
increasing number of local citizens with donations exceeding
800,000 yuan (96,380 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Lu Beila, secretary of the Guangzhou City Charity Federation,
said that the donations are mainly used to help students suffering
a serious illness with insufficient funds for proper health
treatments.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the "Messenger of Charity," Guangzhou citizens
are also active in other charitable activities.
</P>
<P>
They donated more than 8 million yuan (963,850 U.S. dollars) to
build a children's welfare center. In 1996, they donated 5.03
million yuan (606,000 U.S. dollars) to help residents of the
earthquake-hit Lijiang area in Yunnan Province build two middle
schools, one welfare center and a concert hall.
</P>
<P>
"The Light of Charity Evening Party," another major program
launched in the city in 1995, has raised 15 million yuan (1.8
million U.S. dollars) during the past three years.
</P>
<P>
The city charity federation has received more than 70 million
yuan (8.43 million U.S. dollars) in donations since it was set up
in 1994. 
</P>
</TEXT>
