<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Overseas Territories Against Paris Marking End of Slavery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- France's overseas territories are
against Paris' plan for the 150th anniversary of the abolition of
slavery, describing it as hypocrisy and an insult for ex-slaves.
</P>
<P>
The French government is preparing a grand celebration for the
anniversary of the abolition of black slavery in its former
colonies, some of which are now called overseas territories.
</P>
<P>
The Second Republic issued a decree on the abolition on April
27, 1848.
</P>
<P>
However, the people of four major overseas territories -- the
Martinique, Guadeloupe in the Caribbeans, Guyana in the South
American continent, and the Reunion in the Indian Ocean -- are
sceptical and call it "the celebration of former slave owners."
</P>
<P>
The daily Liberation said in an editorial Saturday that France
should not celebrate the event "upside-down," because it should
not only mark those who contributed to the abolition of slavery,
but also should memorize the Africans who were sold from their
homes to servitude in America in three centuries.
</P>
<P>
The inhabitants of the four territories have been calling on
the French government to formally recognize slave trade and
slavery as "crime against humanity."
</P>
<P>
Deeply disappointed by Paris' indifference to their call, they
now feel that the celebration itself is "a slap in the face" and
"a dispossession" for them, said the report.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the United States, which has a tradition of separating
completely blacks from the whites, the French were more tolerant
with a mixture of race between the Africans and the French in
their colonies in America.
</P>
<P>
However, racism and discrimination still persist and are
strongly felt by the descendants of Africans in those territories.
</P>
<P>
"This injury and this sadness are in us and have never been
driven away," said Serge Chalon, a doctor serving the Medecin du
Monde humanitarian group living in Fort-de-France, Martinique.
</P>
<P>
The bitterness is worsened by the erection of a white stone
statue in Martinique in memory of a boat which sank during his
trip from Africa to America, drowning all the African slaves and
slave traders on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
