<HEADLINE> French Oil Group Chief in Congo Republic for Debt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Philippe Jaffre, Chairman and
Managing Director of the French oil group Elf-Aquitaine, visited
the Congo Republic Saturday to discuss the country's huge debt.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with President Denis Sassou-Nguesso in
Brazzaville, Jaffre asked the Congo government to "convince the
fund donors to reschedule the debt," Agence France-Presse reported.
</P>
<P>
With huge interests in the West African oil producing country,
Elf is said to help rebuild the economy devastated last year by a
war between Sassou-Nguesso and his predecessor, Pascal Lissouba.
</P>
<P>
The debt came from the credits provided by world oil groups
investing in Congo and the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Mathias Dzon said the former government of
President Lissouba owed international creditors 357 billion CFA
franc (about 595 million U.S. dollars), almost half the country's
annual oil income.
</P>
<P>
Dzon asked the creditors to reduce by 25 percent of the debt,
the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
