<HEADLINE> Frenchmen More Interested in Pleasure Consumption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Forty-two percent of men and women
in France bought at least one thing in 1997 merely because it
looks good instead of being useful, said a poll published Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In comparison, 34 percent of French people did that in 1994,
said the poll conducted by Cofremca Sociovision research
institution and carried by the daily Aujourd'hui-Le Parisien.
</P>
<P>
Now, more French people are paying for movies, commodities in
secondhand markets, toys and other play things, cafeteria, hotels,
restaurants, books, newspapers, music discs and sports.
</P>
<P>
More than 61 percent of the thousands of people polled in the
latest survey said they are ready to "let off steams" in pleasure
consumption, compared with 54 percent three years ago.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-nine percent said they prefer "flexible working hours"
to higher salaries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
