<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Has More Vets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- When veterinarian Yang Qiqing
got to his clinic in Shanghai every morning, many patients had
been already waiting for him. Extraordinarily, his patients were
not people but cats, dogs, pigeons, parrots, rabbits and monkeys.
</P>
<P>
Yang said his patients usually suffer from cold, enteritis and
dermatitis, and some are plagued by infectious diseases.
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes the owners of the pets ask me to cut down the pets'
nails, or do beauty treatment, or carry out caesarean operation,"
said Yang as he was giving fluid infusion for a two-month-old dog.
</P>
<P>
"Most of the owners are very rich, and they are often at
leisure, and they live in large apartments. Some are foreigners
working in Shanghai, and some are senior citizens living alone,"
said Yang, adding, "They love their pets very much."
</P>
<P>
"Sometimes I was called at mid-night to give emergency
treatment. But I love my job, because I love those little
creatures."
</P>
<P>
Raising pets becomes increasingly popular in this metropolitan
in recent years. Statistics show the number of dogs with license
in the city exceed 50,000. Numerous pet markets, pet shops and pet
hospitals cropped up along streets.
</P>
<P>
Running pet hospital in the city should get appraisal from the
Shanghai Veterinarian Hygiene Inspection Institute, and the pet
doctors should also pass strict examination and get licenses. At
present, the city has more than a dozen pet hospitals, with over
50 qualified pet doctors.  
</P>
</TEXT>
