<HEADLINE> Ugandan Army Inflicts Heavy Losses on Rebels </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Heavy fighting inflicted serious
casualties on the Lord's Resistance Army (LRA) rebels in northern
Uganda in last five days, the New Vision newspaper reported
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The battle broke out last Sunday in Lamwo county, northern
Kitgum District when the Sudan-backed rebels tried to penetrate
further into the district, the official newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
According to Khalil Magara, the Public Relation Officer of the
Fourth Division, the Ugandan army has killed 20 rebels Wednesday
alone.
</P>
<P>
The details of the battle on Thursday are sketchy and
commanders were trying to collect them, Magara added.
</P>
<P>
The captured rebels revealed that the number of invading
rebels is estimated between 200 and 400.
</P>
<P>
The Ugandan army and local defense units in Kitgum and
adjacent Gulu District have been put on full alert since Sunday,
the officer told the paper.
</P>
<P>
Marchall Odur, the regional police commander in the north,
confirmed the battle to the paper and noted that the fighting was
still under way up to Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
LRA is a rebel group active in the northern districts of
Kitgum and Gulu. But it has now only hundreds of remnants and it
has some camps in southern Sudan. In previous years, it had some
2,000 fighters.
</P>
<P>
In another development, an earlier report said, the Allied
Democratic Forces (ADF), another rebel group active in west
Uganda, has been driven by the combined operations of the Ugandan
army and the troops of the Democratic Republic of Congo from the
hideouts in the border areas between the two countries into
Uganda and that will enable the Ugandan army to eradicate them
more easily. 
</P>
</TEXT>
