<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 09:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordan Boasts Highest Per Capita Number of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Jordan, with a population of 4.2
million, boasts the highest per capita number of universities in
the Middle East region, the semi-official English daily Jordan
Times reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The dramatic increase of privately-owned universities during
the past years helps Jordan become the country to boast the
highest per capita number of universities in the region, the
paper quoted Munther Masri, head of Jordan's Human Resource
Development Center and former education minister, as saying.
</P>
<P>
There are now 20 universities - seven public and 13 private -
as well as 50 community colleges in the country, according to
official statistics.
</P>
<P>
Since the country lifted a ban on setting up private
universities in 1993, the number of such universities jumped from
five to 13. In the meantime, the number of publicly-owned
universities stayed stable.
</P>
<P>
The private universities were established to meet the
increasing demand of the influx of foreign students, Masri said.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, with 22 million people, has 13 accredited universities,
while Lebanon and Syria, with populations of 3.4 million and 16
million, respectively, have nine and four universities, according
to the newspaper. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0155 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac to Visit Japan Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac is
scheduled to visit Japan from April 27 to 29.
</P>
<P>
The visit, during Japan's "Year of France" cultural exchange
program starting last year, is to show France's "confidence in and
solidarity with" Japan amid a major economic crisis, said French
presidential spokeswoman Catherine Colonna.
</P>
<P>
Another objective, said Colonna, is to boost France's two
percent share of Japan's market and to cut its five billion franc
(about 800 million U.S. dollar) annual trade deficit with Japan.
</P>
<P>
The negative effects from Japan's economic crisis is being felt
in France, although not as strongly as other European countries,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Chirac will inaugurate the "Statue of Liberty" in the Bay of
Tokyo, a saloon of French farming products in the Japanese
capital, and address the Japanese employers' association Keidaren.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, he will also hold talks with Japanese Prime
Minister Ryutaro Hashimoto and meet Emperor Akihito. 
