<HEADLINE> 80 Suspected Drug Traffickers Arrested in Zambia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- 80 suspected drug traffickers
were arrested in Zambia in the past 10 days, Zambia Daily Mail
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Drugs worth 20.9 million Kwacha (about 11,600 U.S. Dollars)
were seized in the continued crackdown on drug peddlers in the
country, according to the state-owned newspaper.
</P>
<P>
Spokesman of the Drug Enforcement Commission (DEC), Mukutulu
Sinyani, said in Nakonde, northern Zambia Friday that the newly
established Mansa DEC office seized 52 kgs of marijuana, nearly
half of the quantity seized from the 80 suspected traffickers.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 227 grams of opium and 31 tablets of
valium were seized.
</P>
<P>
The threat of cocaine on the copper belt is steadily gaining
momentum, Sinyani said, citing the seizure from illegal peddlers
of 50 milliliters of lidocaine, a component of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
He warned the culprits that the commission will not leave any
stone unturned in combing the streets off the dangerous drug.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Department of Immigration has in the past two
days arrested 26 illegal immigrants in its continued crackdown
operations.
</P>
<P>
Immigration Department Public Relations Official Royn Miyanda
said here Friday that of the arrested, 13 aliens were nabbed in
Kitwe in copper belt.
</P>
<P>
When they were in their operations, the Immigration officials
were almost attacked by a group of foreigners suspectedly mainly
of west African origin.
</P>
<P>
The aliens tried to resist and block the officials from
arresting them.
</P>
<P>
Six were arrested in Lusaka while an American woman has been
ordered to leave Zambia within seven days because she was found
to have over stayed, the spokesman said. 
</P>
