<HEADLINE> Germany Donates 2.5 Million Marks for Refugees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Germany has donated 2.5
million deutsche marks (about 1.35 million US dollars) as an
emergency assistance to refugees from Rwanda, Burundi, the
Democratic Republic of Congo, and the Republic of Congo, Dar es
Salaam newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Citing a statement from the German embassy in Dar es Salaam,
the newspapers said the fund will be used to promote the
repatriation of refugees, provide international protection and
assistance in countries of asylum to refugees who cannot return
home and assist the rehabilitation of refugee-affected areas.
</P>
<P>
The donation was in response to an appeal made by the United
Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR) for assisting
refugees and refugee-affected countries in the Great Lakes region
and west Africa, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
In Tanzania, the fund will assist UNHCR in protecting and
taking care of 330,000 refugees currently in Kigoma and Kagera
regions and preparing provision of assistance to projected 20,000
to 40,000 new refugees who may flow in from Burundi.
</P>
<P>
It will also help the repatriation of some 50,000 refugees to
return to the Democratic Republic of Congo.
</P>
