<HEADLINE> French Press Doubt Over Russia's Stability </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Commenting on the Russian State
Duma's confirmation of Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko, the French
press Saturday expressed doubt over Russia's political stability.
</P>
<P>
The daily Le Figaro said the new cabinet has a hard time: a
dying industry, falling state revenues, angry unpaid workers, a
60-percent deficit in the budget, and a disillusioned middle class.
</P>
<P>
"The success of Boris Yeltsin (in forcing the State Duma, or
the lower house of parliament, to adopt Kiriyenko) is mirrored by
a worrying political landscape: a president weakened by illness
and becoming more and more authoritarian, a fragile prime minister
and a strong parliament," said an article in Le Figaro.
</P>
<P>
By adopting Kiriyenko, said the daily L'Humanite, a great
number of the Russian parliamentary members apparently wished to
keep their posts in the "new nomenclature" rather than risk a
universal suffrage by the Russian people.
</P>
<P>
The people of Russia "could have much to say" if they were
invited to vote, said the daily published by the French Communist
Party. 
</P>
