<HEADLINE> Talks With IMF Successful: Zimbabwean Minister </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The negotiations between the
Zimbabwean government and the International Monetary Fund (IMF)
for financial support were successful, Zimbabwean Minister of
Finance Herbert Murerwa has said.
</P>
<P>
The daily Herald newspaper Saturday quoted Murerwa as saying
the negotiations for three billion Zimbabwean Dollars (180
million U.S. Dollars) standby facility for the balance of
payments support have been successful.
</P>
<P>
The initial disbursement of the money is expected next month,
the paper said.
</P>
<P>
In an interview here Friday, Murerwa said that the
negotiations were concluded in Washington last week and the IMF's
executive board was expected to come up with its final decision
early next month.
</P>
<P>
Murerwa, who led the Zimbabwean delegation to Washington,
dismissed the reports saying that the negotiations had collapsed.
</P>
<P>
He said that everything was still on course.
</P>
<P>
"Our negotiations with the IMF in Washington last week were
very successful," he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that once the IMF board comes up with a decision,
some 875 million Zimbabwean Dollars (51 million U.S. Dollars)
will be made available, while the balance was expected to be
released in tranches based on the end-of-quarter performance
criteria.
</P>
<P>
The IMF has been satisfied with the Zimbabwean government's
budget proposals, which made it possible for the organisation's
board to consider the country's request for the three billion
Zimbabwean Dollars standby arrangement.
</P>
<P>
It had also been agreed that salaries and wages of civil
servants be within the stipulated limits so that they would not
be a drain on the country's financial resources.
</P>
<P>
The minister said an IMF delegation would visit Zimbabwe from
May 19 to 26 this year to be updated on the macro-economic
framework that had been agreed with the Zimbabwean government in
January. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
