<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 07:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Raises Import Duties to Fund Salary </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Cabinet has decided to
increase customs duties on cigarettes by 10 percent and an
across-the-board 2 percent additional tax on other imports as
sources of revenue for the long-delayed salary scales for civil
servants.
</P>
<P>
The decision was announced by Information Minister Bassem
al-Sabaa following a cabinet meeting at the presidential palace
Friday night, the Daily Star newspaper reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Sabaa said customs duties on cigarettes and all tobacco
produce were raised by 10 percent and the more general 2 percent
hike would cover all other imports, including petrol and
industrial raw materials, some of which had been exempted from
customs duties to encourage local industries.
</P>
<P>
He added that the rise in customs duties, which range from 2
percent on necessities to 100 percent on luxury cars, would have
"no impact on the poor class and those with limited income."
</P>
<P>
All civil servants would benefit from the new scales,
including those who would have retired by the time the payments
begin, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
Since Lebanese Parliament endorsed a bill to increase civil
servants' salary starting from January, 1996, the government has
owed 600 billion Lebanese pounds (about 394 million U.S. dollars)
to the employees.
</P>
<P>
Minister of Economy and Trade Yassin Jaber told the newspaper
that the tax increase could raise an annual sum of between 215
billion pounds (about 141 million dollars) and 240 billion
pounds (about 157 million dollars), but additional funds will be
needed to cover the amounts owed since 1996.
</P>
<P>
Sabba said that the government would look into additional
sources of revenue for the salary scales during its regular
session on Wednesday before sending the bill to parliament for
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
By levying the additional taxes now and deferring paying,
government officials said, the government will be better placed
to keep the budget deficit at its forecast level of 42 percent for
1998.
</P>
<P>
This would help improve the country's credit ratings by
international institutions which have given poor ratings to
Lebanon's status, they added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
