<HEADLINE> Corruption Causes Tattered Kenyan Economy: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Kenyan government has no
money and corruption is rampant, leading to the current "tattered
economy" of the country, Finance Minister Simeon Nyachae has
said.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks Friday at a think-tank meeting of
parliamentary members, bankers and foreign donors at the Indian
Ocean port of Mombasa, also Kenya's second-largest city.
</P>
<P>
Corruption in high posts has contributed directly to the
mismanagement of Kenya's financial affairs, making the national
economy in bad shape, the minister was quoted by the daily Nation
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Corruption was holding back economic growth in the east
African country, he admitted.
</P>
<P>
"It was a rare occasion when the government accepted it was
not succeeding in its effort to stamp out corruption," a source
at the meeting said.
</P>
<P>
Nyachae said the government can no longer pay for the bloated
civil service and cuts in this sector must take place "as a
reality" toward breaking the perennial budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
It was not possible to impose more taxes on the people as they
are already overtaxed, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the same day, Governor of the Central Bank of Kenya Micah
Cheserem said in western city Eldoret that the government has
stepped up measures to collect revenue and reduce corruption
which has caused shortage of funds to rehabilitate economy.
</P>
<P>
"The situation is really worrisome. But I am happy that
measures to reverse the trend are being effected seriously," he
claimed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
