<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Sri Lanka Besieged by Postal Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The on-going postal strike in Sri
Lanka has severely affected the country's economy and
administration, government officials said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
About 20,000 postal sorters at the country's Central Mail
Exchange have been on strike since March 11, demanding overtime
pay and other enhanced economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
The overtime boycott-turned-strike has left the country's
postal service nearly paralyzed as millions of letters have been
left undelivered and mail bags piled up at the Colombo harbor and
the Bandaranaike International Airport.
</P>
<P>
At the Central Mail Exchange more than 6 million letters remain
unsorted.
</P>
<P>
Due to the strike, public examinations had to be postponed as
students did not receive their admission cards and timetables. The
strike also interrupted the scheduled sale of public debentures,
local newspapers reported.
</P>
<P>
The worst-affected are pensioners, dependents of those employed
 abroad and police personnel serving in operational areas.
</P>
<P>
Government officials quoted Acting Minister of Posts Anura
Priyadarshana Yapa as saying cabinet ministers and ministry
officials have held protracted talks with the trade unionists in
an effort to end the strike.
</P>
<P>
But the efforts have produced no results as the unionists
changed their stance and added new demands during the talks.
</P>
<P>
The government actually had offered to meet all the demands of
the postal workers, but then the unions insisted on a final
demand, the removal of Postmaster General H. M. S. Kotakadeniya,
which the government rejected.
</P>
<P>
To increase pressure on the unions, President Chandrika
Kumaratunga Friday night promulgated emergency regulations to
declare the postal and telecommunications departments as
"essential services," effective from 06:00 a.m. (local time)
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, security forces and police moved into the
Central Mail Exchange on Friday night and arrested several union
leaders.
</P>
<P>
Workers must return to work Saturday or face consequences under
the emergency regulations, said Kotakadeniya.
</P>
<P>
The consequences may include being forcibly brought to work
under military escort or being detained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0169 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Over 200,000 Rwandans Need Food Aid: WFP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- More than 200,000 Rwandans need
food aid to carry them through to the next harvest in July,
sources at the World Food Program (WFP) said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of people in seven prefectures in the tiny central
African state did not harvest a good crop earlier this year due
to the El Nino-charged rains and flooding over the past several
months, said the WFP Nairobi office.
</P>
<P>
Many of the areas where starvation bites "are traditionally
food-insecure," Gerard van Dijk, WFP's Representative in Rwanda,
was quoted by a WFP report as saying.
</P>
<P>
"Some people in these areas are forced to cultivate on arid
soils or steep slopes as a result of land pressure. Others are
living in villages where there are too many people trying to
survive on too little land," he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, small setbacks in a harvest can be devastating
for these people," he said.
</P>
<P>
WFP's feeding centers there now are filling-up with more
children suffering from varying levels of malnutrition, said the
report.
</P>
<P>
Food prices have dramatically increased over the last few
weeks -- a typical pattern that occurs when the country is
between harvests, said the report.
</P>
<P>
"Prices for staple foods like beans are reaching record
levels," said van Dijk, "On average people are being forced to
pay 30-40 percent more for basic food items compared to last
year. Those living in urban areas are hit hardest since they
have to buy virtually all their food."
</P>
<P>
The U.N. food aid agency now is seeking to increase its
assistance to Rwanda and has given the go-ahead for several new
projects, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
WFP said it is currently providing 3,500 tons of food every
month to 160,000 people in Rwanda. By May the agency hopes to
have raised its aid to more than 5,000 tons reaching some 360,000
Rwandans. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0170 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Drug Dealer Jailed in Zimbabwe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, April 25 (Xinhua) -- A South African woman has been
sentenced to 15 years in prison by Zimbabwe's High Court, the
daily Herald reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Beverly Esabel Parker, a drug courier, was jailed for
unlawfully importing into Zimbabwe cocaine worth more than 1.8
million Zimbabwean Dollars (over 106,000 U.S. Dollars), the
report said.
</P>
<P>
Judge Chinhengo (only one name available) slapped Parker, 28,
with an additional 15,000 Zimbabwean Dollars (880 U.S. Dollars)
fine or in default of payment five years in jail for importing
3.62 kg of cocaine into Zimbabwe from Venezuela via Holland.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwean Police arrested Parker at Harare International
Airport on June 18 last year, following a tip-off by their
counterparts in Holland.
</P>
<P>
Parker was searched and found in possession of the cocaine
which was concealed in 10 sealed tins labeled as "Purina Chunky
dog food."
</P>
<P>
Judge Chinhengo noted that Zimbabwe was a signatory to
international conventions outlawing illicit drug trafficking
which has become a menace in the southern African country.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe has a duty to ensure that its territory is not used
to ship dangerous drugs across territorial boundaries, the judge
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
