<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Pollution Control on Yangtze River (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- China has spent 150 million yuan
(about 18 million US dollars) in building various kinds of
pollution control facilities on the Yangtze River, the longest in
the country, and will invest more funds in the years to come, a
leading environmental protection official said today.
</P>
<P>
Nearly 10,000 meter-long barriers have been built around the
ports and harbors to block the spread of fuel oil from wrecked
ships, and a group of mobile pollution-monitoring stations have
been built and will become operational before June to help
environmental protection authorities keep a close watch on the
river's water quality, said Zhang Tongbin, senior engineer of the
Ministry of Communications.
</P>
<P>
A fleet of large ships for collecting waterborne refuse has
been patroling the river. These ships are also equipped with
wastewater treatment facilities, he added.
</P>
<P>
In another development, a regulation issued jointly by the
Ministry of Communications, Ministry of Construction and the
National Environmental Protection Agency became effective in March
and prohibits vessels on the Yangtze from dumping garbage into the
river.
</P>
<P>
The regulation also calls for a halt to dumping household
garbage and industrial waste along the banks of the river.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River used to be polluted with 30,000 tons of
refuse dumped by ships each year, in addition to more than 360
million tons of liquid containing fuel oil.
</P>
<P>
The Yangtze River, the third longest river in the world, flows
from the west to the east and meanders through 11 provinces and
autonomous regions.
</P>
<P>
The river valley is one of the fastest economic-booming regions
in China, whose gross national product accounting for 40 percent
of the nation's total.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
