<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Strengthens Pollution Control on Yangtze River (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Despite the relatively good water quality in the mainstream of
the river, a pollution belt stretching more than 500 km. has
formed between 25 coastal cities, with increasing water
contamination in many areas," said Peng Biao, senior engineer of
the monitoring center of the Bureau of Protection of Water
Resources in the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
About 15 billion tons of waste water is discharged into the
Yangtze and its tributaries each year, a survey has shown.
</P>
<P>
Thirty-four of the 59 major cities in the valley suffer a water
supply shortage as a result of the pollution, and experts predict
the problem will grow with further economic expansion of the river.
</P>
<P>
Cities in the River valley are paying increasing attention to
the pollution treatment. The city of Shanghai has relocated more
than 800 enterprises from downtown to suburban areas; Chongqing
city has built three waste water treatment plants and closed down
more than 200 small paper mills and coke ovens.
</P>
<P>
The city of Wuhan has introduced funds of 1.7 billion yuan
(about 200 million US Dollars) into urban environmental pollution
treatment, and an urban waste water treatment project has also
been launched.
</P>
<P>
Thirty four large and super-large manufacturing businesses in
eight provinces along the Yangtze River have jointly proposed that
all enterprises along the river reduce their discharge of wastes
and polluting materials into the river at a forum held in January.
</P>
<P>
"The key lies in increasing people's awareness of environmental
protection,"said Zhu Ruming, deputy director of the the shipping
supervisory department of the Yangtze Harbor Superintendency
Administration.
</P>
<P>
Many ships on the river have special personnel to publicize
environmental protection laws and regulations, and they are
authorized to stop crew members and passengers from dumping refuse
into the water. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
