<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Rural Residents in Shanxi Use Clean Toilets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Over one million rural residents
in north China's Shanxi Province have started to use sanitary
toilets instead of traditional ones which used to attract swarms
of flies.
</P>
<P>
For centuries, the old-style latrine was an earthen pit with
two boards on each side and earthen walls standing all around it.
Most rural residents used to build such latrines at a corner of
their courtyards.
</P>
<P>
In some villages of the province, new-style toilets are built
in a designated area, with manure pits underneath.
</P>
<P>
Experts from the provincial health bureau said that the
new-style toilets are clean and can help prevent the spread of
disease.
</P>
<P>
In some places with developed township enterprises, rural
residents have moved into multi-story buildings and they use the
modern toilets as urban residents do.
</P>
<P>
Up to date, farmers in the province's over 100 counties have
been involved in this move.
</P>
<P>
"Toilet Revolution" in Shanxi Province attracted the attention
of the World Health Organization, which sent an investigation team
to the province and decided to launch an "ecological toilet"
campaign in this north China province. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
