<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Fund Used to Curb Sand Shift in Northwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LANZHOU, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Tengger and Badain Jaran deserts
in northwest China's Gansu province witnessed major progress in
shifting sand control, water resources development and grassland
improvement in recent years.
</P>
<P>
With the 1.36 million US dollars of funds from a UN body, the
Gansu provincial government started a project of "harnessing
deserts and promoting agriculture", which made great achievements
in introducing new technology, training personnel and eliminating
poverty.
</P>
<P>
Under the project, a local school of higher learning undertook
22 programs, developed 13 kinds of agriculture technologies, and
improved 20,000 hectares of land for new agriculture products,
benefiting 1,534 peasant families.
</P>
<P>
It also provides various training and 300,000 kilograms of fine
brand seeds to local peasants. The project also improved personnel
quality and research level of the institute, and poured new
elements to traditional agriculture.
</P>
<P>
Due to the project, the living standard of local peasants
largely improved, the average annual income of peasants increased
from 500 yuan at the beginning of the project to the current 1,500
yuan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
