<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Namebrand Garments Winning Bigger Market Share </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The sales volume of China's
name-brand garments is growing fast, thanks to the accelerated
urbanization drive in the country featuring a swelling
white-collar society.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a clothing industry seminar in Beijing, Wang
Zengjing, vice-chairman of the China Garment Society, said that
families with higher income than the country's average will be the
major consumer for name brands.
</P>
<P>
Once a marketplace mainly supported by a big low-income
population, China's garment market is transferring to a maturer
one oriented to the taste of high-income consumers.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that in the next decade, Chinese people's spending on
clothing will further rise, but the increase margin will be
reduced year on year. So, instead of the blue collars, the
families with middle or high incomes will be the most stable
consuming force on the market.
</P>
<P>
According to a statistics report from the State Economic and
Trade Commission, the combined sales volume of the top five brands
in the categories of suit, shirt, jeans, knitted underwear and
duck-down clothing reached a market share of 25 percent or more
last year. The figure for the top five knitted underwear brands
even hit 61.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Wu Yongpeng, president of the Guangdong Pengyun Garment Group,
said that it will be a rather arduous task for Chinese garment
brands to attain global-level reputation. Chinese enterprises have
to develop their own technical edge in addition to the production
scale, so as to survive competition on the international market.
</P>
<P>
As a new technology developed by Wu's company to maintain a
more straight shirt collar, the patent of "PML Magic Collar" was
awarded the golden prize at the '98 China International Garments
and Accessory Exhibition ('98 Chic), which concluded on April 18.
</P>
<P>
Another new technology is the "wooden pulp fiber" presented by
the Rouse Group, a clothing corporation in Zhejiang's Ningbo
City. This patent can largely reduce pollution in clothing
workshops.
</P>
<P>
Liang Yong, director of the organizing committee of '98 Chic,
said that the week-long exhibition, which is only accessible to
hard names from both Chinese and foreign clothing industries, was
attended by 15,000 trade representatives from 26 countries,
registering a direct transaction volume of 2.2 billion yuan and an
indirect one of 3.3 billion yuan.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
