<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High Representative Rejects Possibility for Dayton Revision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The international community's High
Representative Carlos Westendorp has rejected any possibility of
revising the Dayton accord and demanded consistent implementation
of the peace agreement for Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Westendorp's spokesman Simon Haselock was quoted by Hina, the
Croatian news agency, as saying Friday in Sarajevo that the high
representative had carefully considered proposals by Bosnian
Presidency member Kresimir Zubak's chief of staff Martin Raguz and
other Bosnian Croat officials.
</P>
<P>
The officials suggested in recent press articles the
possibility of new divisions inside Bosnia, which Westendorp had
viewed as inconsistent with the Dayton accord.
</P>
<P>
Haselock said Westendorp insisted that the Dayton accord would
remain as the only base for talks on borders, entities and
cantonal divisions, Haselock said.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the Muslim-Croat Federation as an entity
formally established in Dayton was a responsibility for all sides.
</P>
<P>
The high representative will not support any proposals which
would undermine the peace process, Haselock Warned.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of Westendorp, Haselock sent a message to the
initiators of the debate on revising Dayton that they aim their
attention at parts of the peace agreement which concerned
multi-ethnicity, freedom of movement and the rights of all
refugees to return to their homes in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
Adamir Jerkovic, spokesperson for Alija Izetbegovic, chairman
of the Presidency of Alija Izetbegovic, said Friday any
discussions about revisions or amendments to Dayton were
unacceptable to the Muslim side.
</P>
<P>
He said the statements by some Croatian officials questioning
the workings of the Dayton accord were in essence an "anti-package
package".
</P>
<P>
Jerkovic said the Dayton agreement as a compromise achieved
with great efforts laid the foundation for the peaceful
coexistence of different nations in Bosnia-Herzegovina.
</P>
<P>
He said, "We are against any revision of the Dayton agreement,
because it makes a democratic, multiethnic and multicultural
Bosnia-Herzegovina possible."
</P>
<P>
He stressed that the establishment of ethnically pure cantons
in the federation would be an reverse process against civilized
standards, and would also be opposed by the international
community. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
