<HEADLINE> First SAARC Information Ministers' Meeting Begins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Information ministers of the South
Asian Association for Regional Cooperation (SAARC) started their
first meeting here Saturday to discuss ways of increasing
cooperation among member countries of the grouping.
</P>
<P>
"Free flow of information is very important for regional
development," Prime Minister Sheikh Hasina told the inaugural
session of the two-day conference, initiated by Bangladesh at a
SAARC Council of Ministers' meeting in the Maldives last year.
</P>
<P>
Through frequent exchange of information, the standard of
living of about 1.2 billion people in South Asia could be
improved, as "the mass media can play a significant role,
particularly in development," she said.
</P>
<P>
She hoped the SAARC countries would expand cooperation to help
the overall development, progress and peace in the region.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting, Bangladeshi State Minister for Information Abu
Sayeed proposed the establishment of a SAARC information center to
collect, store and disseminate information of the members
countries, a SAARC information research and training center, and a
media development fund to finance training programs and media
organizations.
</P>
<P>
Information ministers from Bangladesh, Pakistan, India, Sri
Lanka and India are attending the meeting, while the Maldives is
represented by a three-member delegation and Bhutan by its Charge
d'Affairs in Dhaka.
</P>
<P>
SAARC, established in December 1985, groups Bangladesh, Bhutan,
India, the Maldives, Nepal, Pakistan and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
</TEXT>
