<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Solar Heaters Help With Grassland Life </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HOHHOT, April 25 (Xinhua) -- "Since we began to use solar
heaters three years ago, we have never lost any animal due to cold
weather," says Bater, a herdsman from a village in the Inner
Mongolia Autonomous Region in north China.
</P>
<P>
Like Bater, all his fellow villagers have set up their own
solar-heated homes to protect the animals from low temperatures
which were a major headache for local herdsmen on the Mongolian
Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Since the 80s, especially in the past two years, local
governments have made efforts to popularize the new technology
among grassland residents.
</P>
<P>
Official figures show that the autonomous region has built up
125,400 square meters of solar-heated residential housing, school
and office buildings, as well as nearly 6.8 million square meters
of solar-heated shelters for animals.
</P>
<P>
An official in charge of the regional office for new energy
says that by the end of this century, Inner Mongolia is expected
to increase its total area of solar-heated buildings to 150,000
square meters and to have eight million square meters of
solar-heated animal shelters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
