<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ADB for Early Devaluation of Indian Rupee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development of Bank
(ADB) has suggested an early devaluation of the Indian rupee to
maintain the country's external competitiveness in the wake of
East Asian currencies' massive depreciation, the Hindustan Times
said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The Indian rupee is now significantly overvalued compared with
the depreciated currencies of Indonesia, South Korea, Malaysia,
the Philippines and Thailand, the newspaper quoted a recent
publication of ADB as saying.
</P>
<P>
The currency devaluations have increased their attractiveness
as locations for foreign direct investment and tourism, the ADB
publication said.
</P>
<P>
ADB has analyzed in details the challenge faced by India's
foreign exchange management in the context of the on-going
economic crisis in Southeast Asia. As exports are rising more
slowly than imports, the trade deficit will widen, leading to a
substantially wider current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
In view of the situation, the Indian authorities must try to
ensure that India's exchange rate remains competitive, ADB said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
