<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0187 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albania Denies Bordering Crashes with Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Albania accused Yugoslavia of
"attempting to shift the responsibility of the Kosovo crisis on to
a foreign country," a statement released by the Albanian Foreign
Ministry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after Yugoslavia announced 16 ethnic Kosovo
Albanians were killed in crashes between Yugoslavia's federal
border troops and some 200 ethnic Albanian gunmen attempting to
re-enter Yugoslavia Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
"There were no border conflicts between the two countries," the
statement said, "the claim of so-called border conflicts by the
Yugoslav government was completely untrue."
</P>
<P>
"The investigation from Albanian special authorities and the
report of the European Union observers group" on
Bosnia-Herzegovina showed that no personnel and arms had entered
Yugoslavia from the Albanian territory, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
"Yugoslavia attempted to deceive the world opinion with the
report of border incidents when the international "contact group"
on Bosnia-Herzegovina will have a meeting scheduled on April 29,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The statement also called on the international community to
immediately react to the Kosovo incident, and reiterated that
Albania will contribute itself to peaceful solution to the Kosovo
crisis.
</P>
<P>
In Belgrade, a communique released earlier Friday by the
headquarters of the general staff of the Yugoslav army said the
Yugoslav army repulsed the attack of the ethnic Albanian gunmen
near Kosara village bordering Albania, and that no Yugoslav
soldiers were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
The frontier troops captured two of the infiltrators and seized
a great deal of weapons and ammunition in the fighting, the
communique said.
</P>
<P>
It said the captured infiltrators confessed they were Kosovo
Albanians who illegally entered Albania, where they received
military training.
</P>
<P>
The Kosovo province of Serbia is populated mainly by ethnic
Albanians demanding independence. In recent months, armed ethnic
Albanian guerrillas have begun fighting against the federal
government. 
</P>
</TEXT>
