<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 19,000 Women Die in Pregnancy Annually in Bangladesh </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- About 19,000 Bangladeshi women die
annually due to pregnancy-related complications aggravated by
malnutrition, local media reported on Saturday, quoting experts.
</P>
<P>
As high as 70 percent of mothers suffer from iron deficiency
anemia and 46 percent have low body mass index, UNICEF (the United
Nations Children's Fund) experts Yuki Shiroshi and T.O.
Kyaw-Myintwhile told a seminar in Dhaka Friday.
</P>
<P>
The seminar, organized by UNICEF, was part of the ongoing
nutrition week in this South Asian county.
</P>
<P>
Around 25 percent maternal deaths are associated with anemia
and hemorrhage, Professor A.K.M. Nurul Anwar said at the seminar,
adding that malnutrition is inherited by about 50 percent of the
new-borns.
</P>
<P>
The maternal mortality rate in Bangladesh is 4.5 per 1,000
births and is among the highest in the world, Joint secretary of
the Health Ministry Misanur Rahman said.
</P>
<P>
There are 890 private and public hospitals in the country with
a total of 34,786 beds, and the bed-population ratio is
approximately 1:3,450, according to Rahman.
</P>
<P>
The country has produced 24,638 graduate doctors over the past
two decades and the doctor-population ratio now stands at 1:4,870.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
