<HEADLINE> Durable Goods Consumption Expanding in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- By the year 2000, 8 million to
10 million households in China will be able to buy their own cars.
</P>
<P>
The figure will rise to 85 million involving a population of
300 million, or a quarter of the country's total population, by
2010.
</P>
<P>
The prediction was made by some Chinese and foreign experts at
an international seminar on consumption in China being held in
Changsha, capital of central China's Hunan Province.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the sales of cars to individuals were
40,500 in the mid-1960s. It increased to 1.47 million in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The experts noted that the consumption of other durable goods
also expanded rapidly in recent years.
</P>
<P>
China's output of refrigerator increased from 49,000 in 1980 to
9.79 million in 1996; the washing machine from 49,000 to 10.74
million; and television sets from 2.49 million to 35.4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
