<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Artificial Fertilization Helps Breed Rare Fox </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARBIN, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists successfully
applied artificial fertilization for breeding a precious genus of
fox -- frosty-blue fox.
</P>
<P>
So far, more then 1,000 Chinese female blue foxes have given
birth to frosty-blue foxes with artificially fertilized sperm from
imported super silver male foxes from Finland.
</P>
<P>
China has established over a dozen frosty-fox breeding centers
nationwide and targets to breed 300,000 foxes of the genus by
2000, in an effort to boost its high-value added fur industry.
</P>
<P>
Kong Qinsong, an expert incharge of frosty-blue fox breeding,
said fox is one of the three kinds of animals that could produce
fur for coat-making. It has a great market demand.
</P>
<P>
He said though China now breeds more than 400,000 foxes, most
of them are small and frosty-blue fox fur coats enjoy a high price
in the domestic and overseas markets.
</P>
<P>
The development was achieved by Chinese scientists at the Wild
Animal Resources College of Northeast China Foresty University
after 10 years research. To cater to the needs of growing market,
they began research in 1988.
</P>
<P>
So far, the pregnancy rate of the artificially fertilized
female foxes reached 88 percent and each female fox could give
birth to eight baby foxes at a time on the average.
</P>
<P>
Experts said the spreading of the technique can reduce the cost
of fox breeding as the number of male foxes could be cut sharply.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
