<HEADLINE> Vietnam Launches Campaign Against AIDS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's National AIDS Committee
has launched a nationwide campaign to stem the rapid spread of
AIDS and improve the treatment of patients, the local press
reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In Executing the campaign, the government will make efforts to
give medical care to 70 percent of carriers of the HIV, the virus
that causes the deadly disease of AIDS, and prevent the spread of
AIDS in the country.
</P>
<P>
To raise the nation's AIDS awareness, the National AIDS
Committee has taken a promotional initiative across the country.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, by April 18 this year, 8,530
HIV cases had been detected across the country and it is estimated
that there are over 1200 pregnant women contracting the HIV virus
each year.
</P>
<P>
Ho Chi Minh City has the largest number of HIV carriers and the
northern province of Quang Ninh the next, the statistics said.
</P>
<P>
Most of the newly-detected HIV carriers are identified as
teenage drug abusers.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, the government has asked for international
assistance to fight the spread of AIDS in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
In response, organizations under the United Nations have
decided to grant Vietnam two million U.S. dollars annually from
this year until 2000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
