<HEADLINE> Home Electronic Appliances to Become New Rural Consumer Focus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- In a few years, home electronic
appliances will become a new consumer focus in rural areas,
predicted a Chinese economist.
</P>
<P>
Yin Shijie, a consumption specialist, told a seminar held
recently here that a survey showed that 22 percent of the families
in rural China intend to buy color televisions, as compared with
20 percent of urban families, and the proportion of rural and
urban families wanting to purchase washing machines remain more or
less the same at 16 percent.
</P>
<P>
The gap is large only concerning the purchase of cars and
cellular phones, the survey said.
</P>
<P>
At present, about 20 percent of Chinese rural families possess
washing machines, less than 10 percent of them have refrigerators,
and 88 percent own televisions -- mostly of black and white screen.
</P>
<P>
According to statistics, in 1996, the net per capita rural
income averaged about 1,900 yuan (228.9 US dollars), which was
only about one third of the urban income.
</P>
<P>
According to the study by Yin, in five years, the rural
consumption level can catch up with the present urban level. And
if so, the rural areas will need 10 million sets of new
radio-recorders, and about 150 million sets of color television,
refrigerators, and washing machines respectively.
</P>
<P>
Many manufacturers are developing energy-saving and low-priced
machines to cater to the growing need. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
