<HEADLINE> Kuwait to Buy F/A-18 Jets From Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Kuwait has agreed in principle to
take over a squadron of eight F/A-18 Hornet fighter jets from
Thailand, Supreme Commander Gen. Mongkol Ampornpisith said.
</P>
<P>
Gen. Mongkol made the announcement after a meeting with
Kuwait's representative Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad Al-Sabah, who is
also president of the Olympic Council of Asia.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad arrived in Thailand on Thursday to follow
up progress in Thailand's preparation for the Asian Games.
</P>
<P>
"Sheikh Ahmad has stressed clearly that Kuwait will purchase
the fighters," Gen. Mongkol told reporters.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Ahmad Al-Fahad said after the meeting that the decision
to procure the two-engine jet fighters from the Royal Thai Air
Force would be in line with Kuwait Air Force's modernization plan.
</P>
<P>
The Royal Thai Air Force has set a 74.5-million-U.S.-dollar
deposit for its 392-million-dollar purchase of the fighters from
the American firm Boeing.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton agreed in March to allow Thailand
to cancel the deal because of Thailand's economic crisis and
decided not to impose a 250-million-dollar fine for the
cancellation.
</P>
<P>
However, the U.S. made it clear that Thailand would not get its
deposit back unless it resells the jets to a third party. 
</P>
