<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Plans to Produce More Gold in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Peru plans to produce 86 tons of
gold this year, 13 percent more than last year's production of 76
tons, despite lower gold prices on the international market.
</P>
<P>
The Gold Committee of Peru's Mining and Oil National Society
(SNMP) said Friday that Peru's gold production grew more than 10
percent in the first quarter of the year.
</P>
<P>
The committee said Peru could achieve by the year 2003 an
annual output of over 100 tons because of increasing investment
in exploration and the development of new projects.
</P>
<P>
A total of 480 million U.S. dollars is expected to be invested
in prospecting in 1998, despite the serious drop in the
international gold quotations.
</P>
<P>
The Barrick Gold firm is planning the biggest investment this
year with its Pierina Project due to start production before the
end of 1998, at a rate of 750,000 ounces a year.
</P>
<P>
Investment in the Minera Yanacocha company continues, with its
production surpassing one million ounces a year.
</P>
<P>
The SNMP said that although last year's gold output grew 18
percent over 1996, less income was obtained because of the drop in
the market quotation of the metal, which fell from 388 dollars an
ounce to 331 dollars on average.
</P>
<P>
The country produced close to 800 million U.S. dollars worth of
gold in 1997, and exported 500 million dollars worth in the form
of refined metal or contained in concentrates, and the remaining
40 percent was exported as manufactured products.
</P>
<P>
Production of this year may reach 900 million U.S. dollars,
the SNMP estimated.
</P>
<P>
It predicted a stable or even better outlook for gold prices,
now about 310 U.S. dollars an ounce, up from 270 dollars in the
previous months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
