<HEADLINE> FAO Backs Cuban Plan for Aquaculture Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAVANA, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Food and Agriculture
Organization (FAO) backs a Cuban plan of cooperation in the
aquaculture sector "of which the impact must be immediate for
producers" in this island, the FAO representative office said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Cuba, the sixth biggest Latin American country in the
development of aquaculture, will have rapid access to modern
technology of feed for edible fish thanks to this FAO project,
valued at 147 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The plan foresees a substantial increase in the volume of fish
produced through the intensive or semi-intensive cultivation, and
plans to substitute imported fish with local products, and will
have positive repercussions on the supply of fish for domestic
consumption.
</P>
<P>
The Mamposton Center of Aquaculture Preparation in the Havana
province, a branch of the Fishing Industry Ministry, will execute
the FAO project on the Cuban side.
</P>
<P>
This international organization has also collaborated in the
war against the auger worm of cattle and the Thrips Plami plague
that attacked cultivations in the nation last year. 
</P>
