<HEADLINE> Venice in Peril from Sea, Needing Urgent Action </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Italy's Venice, the "Queen of the
Adriatic", is in peril as the sea level of the Mediterranean keeps
increasing, but there is still time to save it, a Italian expert
said Friday.
</P>
<P>
Roberto Frassetto, chairman of the Italian Committee on Global
Change, made the remark after a London-based Venice in Peril
Committee issued a report earlier this week, warning that Venice,
one of the world's most beautiful cities, could be swallowed up by
the sea one day unless urgent preventive action is taken now.
</P>
<P>
The report said that although the flooding which occurred in
1966 has not recurred, the city nevertheless is in increasing
danger as the tides swell higher each year. The committee called
on the Italian government to act now before it is too late.
</P>
<P>
Frassetto downplayed what he called the "overly catastrophic"
terms used by one of the British scholars in the report, which
were quickly disseminated in the world press.
</P>
<P>
Venice did run "enormous risks" due to the fact that changes in
climate were expected to raise the level of the Mediterranean 20
centimeters over the next 50 years and 60 centimeters in a
century, Frassetto conceded.
</P>
<P>
However, he added that the experience of Britain and the
Netherlands showed that prevention can avert a disaster which
would otherwise be of incalculable proportions.
</P>
<P>
The document approved in London bears the signature not only of
Frassetto himself but of those responsible for the defense of the
British capital against the perils posed by the River Thames and
for the protection of the Netherlands from encroachment by the North
Sea.
</P>
<P>
The equivalent of millions of dollars has been spent in
preventive work over a decade and it was becoming clear to
everyone that this investment had begun to bear fruit, both in
England and in the Netherlands, Frassetto said.
</P>
<P>
Such prevention was urgently needed for Venice too if it was
not to drown in an ever rising sea overwhelming its lagoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
