<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Govt Tries to End Postal Strike </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lanka government has used
emergency regulations to try to force an end to a 44-day long
postal strike, official media said Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
President Chandrika Kumaratunga Friday night promulgated
Emergency Regulations to declare the Postal and Telecommunication
Services "Essential Services" effective from 06:00 a.m. (local
time) Saturday.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night, contingents of security forces were sent to
take control of both the new and old Central Mail Exchanges, where
police arrested 10 postal union leaders.
</P>
<P>
The union leaders were being detained at different police
stations in the city.
</P>
<P>
Postmaster General H.M.S.Kotakadeniya said those who failed to
report for work would be dealt with according to the emergency
rules, under which they would be forcibly brought to work under
military escort and would be detained for further action if they
resist.
</P>
<P>
The striking postal workers have yet to issue a statement
following the arrest of their leaders.
</P>
<P>
The postal strike began on March 11 when postal workers
demanded overtime pay and other enhanced economic benefits.
Protracted discussions with the government resulted in all issues
being settled, but by then the workers had included a final demand
for the removal of the postmaster general.
</P>
<P>
The demand was rejected and the strike is continuing.  
</P>
</TEXT>
