<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Government to Cut Staff by 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Thai government plans to cut
the civil service workforce by 10 percent in the next four years
as part of a sweeping bureaucratic reform, according to a source
at the Thai Government House.
</P>
<P>
The cutback was proposed by the Bureaucratic Reform Committee,
headed by deputy prime minister Bhichai Rattakul.
</P>
<P>
Under the proposal, from now until the year 2001 the government
will not increase civil service positions, and will also dissolve
80 percent of all the positions vacated by retirees every year.
</P>
<P>
A central workforce committee will then be in charge of
distributing the remaining 20 percent of the vacancies to state
agencies in dire need of positions for new staff. The remaining
posts after the distribution will be scrapped.
</P>
<P>
The cutback was needed due to a rapid increase in the size of
the government workforce, the source was quoted Saturday by the
Bangkok Post as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to a government survey, the government workforce
nationwide stood at 1,032,802 in 1981, and rose to 1,464,557 in
1995. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
