<HEADLINE> Clinton Nominates New Nuclear Command </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
has nominated Vice Admiral Richard Mies, a Navy submarine
commander, to take charge of the U.S. Strategic Command, the
Pentagon announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
If confirmed by the Senate, Mies, 54, would replace Air Force
General Eugene Habiger, who has applied to retire effective August
1, the Pentagon said.
</P>
<P>
The Strategic Command, located at Offutt Air Force Base in
Omaha, Nebraska, is in charge of planning for potential nuclear
confrontation, analytical studies for strategic nuclear policy and
arms control.
</P>
<P>
Mies, a three-star admiral, currently serves as commander of
the U.S. submarine force in the Atlantic and as NATO's top
submarine commander in the Atlantic, based in Norfolk, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
He is a native of Chicago and graduated from the U.S. Naval
Academy in 1967. 
</P>
</TEXT>
