<HEADLINE> (Updated) U.S. Welcomes Kiriyenko Confirmed as </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, April 24 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Friday welcomed the Russian parliament's confirmation of Boris
Yeltsin's candidate Sergei Kiriyenko as Russia's new prime
minister.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a ceremony at the White House,
Clinton said he hoped the breakthrough vote would lead to Russian
ratification of the stalled START II nuclear arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good news day for Russia and for the United States,"
Clinton said. "We have a high opinion of him," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I also very much hope this will free up the Duma to consider
the START II treaty because if they will ratify it, then we can
move on to START III and continue our effort of dramatically
reducing the nuclear threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, 35, was confirmed Friday by Russia's Duma as the new
prime minister after rejecting him twice.
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, Vice President Al Gore congratulated Kiriyenko in
a telephone call. They agreed to meet this summer.
</P>
<P>
Gore and Kiriyenko also agreed that the U.S.-Russia
Commission set up by Gore and Kiriyenko's predecessor, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, would continue its work on U.S-Russian issues.
</P>
<P>
White House spokesman Mike McCurry said that the U.S. looks
forward to and expects to have "a close working relationship"
with Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin told a briefing that
Kiriyenko "clearly signals the kind of generational change that
is necessary around the world."
</P>
<P>
"He's well and favorably known in Washington," said Rubin.
</P>
</TEXT>
