<HEADLINE> Brazil Speaks on U.N. Chief's Report on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The international
community must not lose sight of the universal dimension of its
individual character in dealing with Africa, Brazilian delegate
Celso Amorim said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the United Nations Security Council's open debate
on the U.N. chief's report on Africa, Amorim said the report of
the secretary-general was an objective analysis with thoughtful
recommendations which called for cafeful examination not only by
the Security Council, but also by the General Assembly, the
Economic and Social Council and other components of the United
Nations system.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said consistency was needed in the search for
solution to areas in crisis in Africa. The United Nations had been
instrumental in bringing peace and relief to many areas in Africa,
either through peacekeeping or through manifold programs directed
at improving the lives of the neediest, he added.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, those efforts remained insufficient. The
problem was not only one of resources. There was a qualitative
dimension to be kept in mind. Technical assistance, for instance,
could not be "supply oriented" but must be targeted to the
specific needs of the recipient countries and should make full use
of their resources and potentialities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
