<HEADLINE> West African Nations Want to See More Foreign Investment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- West African states want
to see more foreign direct investment into their economies to
enhance their diversification of traditional exports essential to
their sustained growth.
</P>
<P>
This point of view was expressed by Nigeria's Permanent
Representative to the United Nations Ibrahim Gambari who spoke
here Friday on behalf of the Economic Community of West African
States (ECOWAS) at a U.N. debate on Africa.
</P>
<P>
However, the effectiveness of the investment would depend on
the alleviation by the international community of the external
debt burden of heavily indebted African countries, he told the
debate on U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan's recent report on
Africa.
</P>
<P>
Africa's external debt totaled 328.9 billion U.S. dollars in
1995, according to U.N. statistics.
</P>
<P>
He said the ECOWAS believes that the Bretton Woods institutions
have a key role to play in the promotion of peace in Africa.
</P>
<P>
These institutions should develop "Peace-Friendly" Structural
Adjustment Programs which do not undermine the ability of African
governments to fulfill their basic responsibilities in people's
education, health and welfare, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
