<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania: Int'l Community Should Consider Further </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The international
community should seriously consider the U.N. secretary-general's
proposal to examine further additional actions on the debt facing
Africa, particularly of the least developed countries, Tanzanian
delegate Daudi Mwakawago said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Mwakawago said the result of well-meant programs such as the
Heavily Indebted Poor Countries Debt Initiative of the Bretton
Woods Institutions has proven disappointing. And yet Africa
continues to face the crippling debt burden at a time when even
the frailest economies have just recently been ravaged by the
vagaries of the El Nino phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
The delegate said that while Africa does not desire to dishonor
its debt obligations, a cancellation of such debt burden would
release and make available to Africa critical resources it needs
to build appropriate infrastructure for its prosperity and peace.
</P>
<P>
He expressed the hope that the Security Council will work not
only with African countries, but also with the Organization of
African Union, in addressing the twin goals of peace and security
on the one hand, and development on the other in Africa. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
