<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> European Union Welcomes U.N. Chief's Report on Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The European Union
applauds the U.N. secretary-general's report on Africa, which
bring together many ideas and approaches as a comprehensive policy
towards Africa at a particularly opportune time, John Weston,
Britain's permanent representative to the U.N. said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking on behalf of the European Union at the open debate of
the U.N. Security Council on Africa, Weston said the
secretary-general has provided a clear and candid analysis of the
sources of conflict in Africa and the reasons why they persist.
</P>
<P>
Weston said the report contains concrete recommendations on
ways to prevent and address conflicts in Africa, and how to lay
the foundations for subsequent durable peace. The historic
approach is most welcome, and the European Union looks forward to
further comprehensive discussion of the report, he added.
</P>
<P>
The representative said the European Union supports the
secretary-general's recommendations that the United Nations
develops closer relations with African regional and sub-regional
organizations and arrangements, and also supports increased
cooperation between the U.N. and Sub-regional organizations in the
areas of conflict prevention, management and resolution.
</P>
<P>
He said the European Union welcomes the U.N. chief's call for
all African countries to participate in the U.N. register of
conventional arms. The European Union will continue to support
efforts aimed at the establishment of effective national control
measures on the transfer of conventional arms, combating illegal
arms trafficking and the banning and clearing of anti-personnel
landmines.
</P>
<P>
Weston said the European Union welcomes the emphasis placed in
the secretary-general's report on the further development of
regional cooperation and integration among African countries
across a wide range of different fields, and on the importance of
creating an environment where durable peace is sustained and
economic growth promoted.
</P>
<P>
The European Union believes, he said, that it is imperative
that the political momentum generated by this report must not be
lost, and is committed to working to ensure that Africa remains on
the international agenda at the highest level. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
