<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, April 25 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton Friday welcomed the
Russian parliament's confirmation of Boris Yeltsin's candidate
Sergei Kiriyenko as Russia's new prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters during a ceremony at the White House,
Clinton said he hoped the breakthrough vote would lead to Russian
ratification of the stalled START II nuclear arms treaty.
</P>
<P>
"This is a good news day for Russia and for the United States,"
Clinton said. "We have a high opinion of him," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"I also very much hope this will free up the Duma to consider
the START II treaty because if they will ratify it, then we can
move on to START III and continue our effort of dramatically
reducing the nuclear threat," he said.
</P>
<P>
Kiriyenko, 35, was confirmed Friday by Russia's Duma as the new
prime minister after rejecting him twice. (US-Russia-Reaction)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The European Union's decision to drop a World
Trade Organization (WTO) complaint against the U.S. over an
anti-Cuba U.S. law may improve chances for a possible agreement in
the controversy, the State Department said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"Certainly the fact that the decision was made not to go
forward with a case before the WTO indicates desire on the
Europeans' part to come to a solution," said State Department
spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
"But the next step is to see whether we can come to an
understanding that no country should want to see expropriated
property benefit the expropriator," said Rubin.
</P>
<P>
The Helms-Burton law was enacted in 1996 after two small U.S.
planes was shot down by the Cuban military when they flew into
Cuba's skies. (US-Cuba-EU)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The European Union (EU) Friday expressed grave
concern over the renewed violence in Kosovo, Yugoslavia, appealing
for "meanful dialogue" between the parties concerned.
</P>
<P>
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, whose country is the
current EU president, said in a statement on behalf of the
15-nation bloc: "We are deeply concerned by the reports of renewed
violence in Kosovo and in particular of increasing activity by the
Yugoslav army."
</P>
<P>
It was reported that the Serbian security forces killed 22
guerilla infiltrators from neighboring Albania over the past few
days. (UK-EU-Kosovo) 
</P>
