<HEADLINE> Italian Premier Insists on Lowering Mortgage Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Italian Premier Romano Prodi Friday
reiterated his government's commitment to bringing Italy's
mortgage interest rates down to five percent.
</P>
<P>
The declaration came in the midst of a heated dispute over the
reluctance of commercial banks to lower their rates in the wake of
the Bank of Italy's discount rate reduction on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
During question time in the Lower House, Prodi said he was
satisfied with his government's involvement with banks and credit
institutions aimed at rolling back mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
"When I talked of the dream of five percent, the rate was 14
percent and now it is 6.25 percent. I think we can get there in a
fairly short time," the premier said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the five percent mortgage is a feature of
civilization, a way for workers to have a home.
</P>
<P>
Also Friday, Cabinet Undersecretary Enrico Micheli said the
banking system had to attain greater efficiency to help pave the way
to greater flexibility on mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
Referring to reports that banks said they would be unable to
meet the five percent goal without government subsidies, Micheli
said he could rule out "state aid."
</P>
<P>
What was needed, he said, was "the independent action of the
banks" because subsidies were "old and outdated." 
</P>
