<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0242 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Free of Quake Damage in Immediate Future </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- Earthquakes rating 4 to 5 on the
Richter scale and jolting areas neighboring Beijing will not cause
damage to the city although they may fuel panic and rumors,
today's China Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
"A quake measuring 4-5 on the Richter scale is not strong
enough to damage the city's buildings, for most of the public and
residential buildings were constructed to withstand quakes of 6
degrees," said Ding Jianhai, director of the Department of
Earthquake Prediction's Center for Analysis and Prediction under
the State Seismological Bureau.
</P>
<P>
According to Ding, round-the-clock feedback from the city's
quake prediction stations has ruled out the possibility of quakes
over 5 on the Richter scale in the immediate future.
</P>
<P>
Beijing boasts China's most sophisticated quake-prediction
network with more than 50 prediction stations, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
But rumor and panic about the potential of large-scale quakes
have been aroused by a 6.2 quake which hit Zhangjiakou near the
Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake killed 50 people, injured thousands and brought
down 100,000 houses.
</P>
<P>
The tension mounted when a 4.7 quake on April 14 hit Tangshan
in north China's Hebei Province, 175 kilometers from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
The official said minor quakes may occur in the quake-active
circle including Tangshan, Zhangjiakou and Tianjin, and can be
felt in Beijing, which is located on the verge of the circle.
</P>
<P>
"The capital will not be the epicenter of quakes in the
quake-prone circle. You may feel it when quakes come, but that's
all," the official said.
</P>
<P>
Historical files indicate that nine quakes measuring over 6 on
the Richter scale have jolted Beijing and its neighboring areas
since AD 438. The first one struck the south part of Beijing in
1057. The city has no record of quakes of over 7 degrees.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the bureau also indicate that ten localities
across the country might well be hit by medium or strong quakes
this year. Local governments have been called on to take advanced
anti-quake measures.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said China is now going through its fifth active
quake period of the century, lasting from late 1988 to the
beginning of the next century.
</P>
<P>
The mainland and offshore areas recorded eight earthquakes
measuring 6 and above on the Richter scale from 1988 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
China has successfully predicted two earthquakes of over 6
degrees in Menglian County in southwest China's Yunnan Province in
1995 and Jiashi area in northwest China's Xinjiang Uygur
Automonous Region.
</P>
<P>
Last year, several powerful tremors in the northwestern area of
Xinjiang killed more than 50 people.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Dealing With Unemployment Problem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- People from all circles in China
are asked to help unemployed workers.
</P>
<P>
In China's most populous province, Henan, labor departments say
they will train 200,000 laid-off workers this year and find
employment for 70 percent of them. The province also decided to
give preferential loans to laid-off workers so that they can start
their own businesses, and to subsidize enterprises that want to
employ the unemployed.
</P>
<P>
In Tianjin, the biggest port city in northern China, 59
reemployment centers have been set up and job firms of the
municipal trade union council give free aid.
</P>
<P>
The municipal trade union council also conducts a monthly
survey of unemployed workers' living conditions, and has
established 20,000 files on people needing special help.
</P>
<P>
In Jiangsu, one of China's most economicly developed provinces,
nearly 200 training bases for laid-off workers have been
established and those who have lost their jobs can draw relief
money from the provincial government.
</P>
<P>
In Liaoning province, where there are many state-owned
enterprises, many colleges and polytechnic schools have decided to
provide free training for laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
China's Education Ministry recently asked 1,000 universities
and colleges, 700,000 middle and primary schools and other
vocation and polytechnic schools to do something for the laid-offs.
</P>
<P>
The Youth League, China's largest mass organization for young
people, also plans to help 100,000 laid-off workers find
employment in the next several years.
</P>
<P>
Ministry of Labor sources say that through the year 2000, the
country will organize training for 10 million laid-off workers and
this year China will try to employ at least 60 percent of the
laid-off workers.
</P>
<P>
In May the State Council will hold a working conference on the
issue.
</P>
<P>
China has more than 10 million laid-off workers. According to
the Ministry of Labor, in the next three years the employment
situation in China could worsen, as 8 to 10 million more workers
will leave their jobs and wait for reemployment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
