<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy, Sweden, Britain Sign Job Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Italy, Sweden and Britain signed two
job creation pacts in Venice Friday to provide jobs for unemployed
people in the three countries and train them with a second
language.
</P>
<P>
Labor Ministers from the three states said under the
agreements, 150 jobless people from each country will be trained
in foreign languages and sent to work abroad.
</P>
<P>
The initiative, said Italian Labor Minister Tiziano Treu,
originated with the special European Union employment summit held
in Luxembourg last year.
</P>
<P>
British Labor Minister Andrew Smith said, "The initiative will
take off within the year, following the definition of criteria for
the selection of candidates, access to the program and the types
of enterprise and work which will be covered."
</P>
<P>
Swedish Labor Minister Margareta Winberg said her country
intends to make certain that young people above 25 are without
work for no longer than 100 days.
</P>
<P>
Treu said the pacts are the first joint efforts to resolve the
unemployment problem within Europe and may be expanded to other
European countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
