<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Operatic Drama "Peony Pavilion" to Make Global Tour (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, April 25 (Xinhua) -- People all over the world will
have a chance to see the operatic dream "Peony Pavilion", created
by Chinese playwright Tang Xianzu (1550-1616) about 400 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The 55-act Chinese opera will make its American debut on July 7
at New York's Lincoln Center in a 20-hour show spreading over six
nights. It will be performed by the Shanghai Kunqu Opera Troupe
under the direction of Chen Shizheng, a Chinese artist living in
New York.
</P>
<P>
The audience will be given a look at: a young woman's dream of
meeting her perfect match; a young man's dream of finding his
lover at the Peony Pavilion; the young woman's death; the young
man's pursuit of her ghost; the woman's resurrection; and finally,
their reunion after battles with the Judge of Hell.
</P>
<P>
"The opera is an epic spectacle that rolls out like a giant
Chinese scroll painting," Chen explains, and in his production, 22
actors and actresses will play 106 roles of Mongol invaders,
bandits, Taoist nuns, scholars, prostitutes, and a host of
others.
</P>
<P>
Chen is attempting to give the audience a look at the ancient
Chinese theater at the time of Tang Xianzu -- a contemporary of
Shakespeare and as great a creative force -- at a total cost of
500,000 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
There will be no wings or backdrops on the stage. The orchestra
will sit in full view of the audience and actors and actresses put
on make up and change costumes on stage, and on both sides of the
audience there will be bird cages with live birds, and the
performers will fish in a real fish pond at the front of the stage.
</P>
<P>
Actors and actresses who have finished their parts will mix and
chat with the audience, and at any time during the performance,
the audience can go to the lobby to get something to eat or drink.
</P>
<P>
Chen believes that this new type of drama will provide the
audience with a kind of relaxed enjoyment and give an
understanding of what real life, society, and people were like in
ancient China.
</P>
<P>
Tang lived at a time when the dominant philosophy was "Li Xue"
(Neo-Confucianism), a school of philosophy that taught that people
should regulate their behavior in accordance with feudal
propriety, says Sun Jiaxiu, director of the China Shakespeare
Research Insitute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980425.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Operatic Drama "Peony Pavilion" to Make Global Tour (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, Tang sought the liberation of individuality in his
works, and tried to celebrate love to counter feudal morality and
ethics, Sun says, adding, "Both Tang and Shakespeare's works fully
express the humanistic ideas of love -- the undying themes of both
Oriental and Occidental theater." And, he thinks that "Peony
Pavilion" will receive a warm welcome from foreign audience.
</P>
<P>
Kunqu Opera is one of China's classical operatic forms, which
originated in the Kunshan region of Jiangsu Province about 500
years ago. After centuries of development, it has established a
complete system of acting as well as its own distinct tunes.
</P>
<P>
The music and acting of Kunqu Opera have had a significant
influence on other traditional Chinese operatic forms, including
Peking Opera.
</P>
<P>
Wu Shuqin, of the Ministry of Culture, says that "Peony
Pavilion" has remained an important part of the repertoire of both
Chinese Kunqu and Peking Opera troupes.
</P>
<P>
"The opera was written about 400 years ago, but there is no
record in history of a complete performance of the whole opera,"
she added.
</P>
<P>
So, to reflect the tradition of ancient music on stage, Chen
decided to transcribe the original music into modern musical
notation according to a score for the opera in the Qing Dynasty
(1644-1911).
</P>
<P>
"Peony Pavilion" will also appear at the Paris Autumn Arts
Festival in November, the Sydney Arts Festival, and the Hong Kong
Arts Festival next January.
</P>
<P>
A Western opera production of "Peony Pavilion" is also in
rehearsal by artists in the United States to match Chen's Kunqu
Opera in the Lincoln Center Arts Festival.
</P>
<P>
"Chinese people often say Tang is as great as his contemporary
Shakespeare, but we have never shown his greatness to the world,"
Sun says, but now, people outside China are beginning to show an
interest in the art of this interesting Asian dramatist whose
works have been available in English for some time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
