<HEADLINE> Serbia Says No to Foreign Mediation Over Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, April 24 (Xinhua) -- Final results of the referendum
held on Thursday showed an overwhelming majority of voters
rejected foreign mediation over Kosovo, General Secretary of
Serbian Referendum Organizing Committee Nebojsa Rodic said here
Friday.
</P>
<P>
Rodic told a press conference that about 95 percent of the
voters cast a "NO" vote while only 3.4 percent of the poll goers
favored foreign mediation efforts over the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
Rodic confirmed the validity of the results by saying that the
voter turnout in the referendum totaled about 5.3 million and
accounted for about 73 percent of registered voters.
</P>
<P>
He said that the results showed that the absolute majority
backed the Kosovo policies adopted by the country's leaders.
</P>
<P>
The Politika daily said on Thursday that the voters supported
the principled stand of Yugoslav and Serbian leaders that Kosovo
is an inseparable part of Serbia and the issue is an internal
affair which should be settled by political means.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking on Thursday at a polling booth in Belgrade,
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic said all ethnic groups in
the country could and must solve their problems by themselves for
common interests.
</P>
<P>
Milosevic urged leaders of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to open
talks with Serbian representatives as soon as possible, and hoped
that the Serbian authorities be fully sincere in the talks.
</P>
<P>
Ethnic Albanian leaders in Kosovo have repeatedly refused to
meet the Serbian government delegation unless foreign
representatives are present.
</P>
<P>
At least 80 ethnic Albanians and Serb policemen have been
killed since ethnic conflicts broke out in the Serbian province in
late February. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
