<HEADLINE> Indonesia Sets Working age at 15 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, April 25 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
revised upward the legal work age to 15 years and above, from 10
years previously, in a bid to reduce child labor and keep more
young people in school, a senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The move to return children aged less than 15 years to school
will be implemented in stages in the next five years,"
Coordinating Minister for People's Welfare Haryono Suyono said
Friday when announcing the decision at a meeting.
</P>
<P>
The program is part of the nine-year compulsory education
program, local leading newspapers reported Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Official data show there are about 2.1 million children working
nationwide. The country's population currently stands at 202
million, and children between eight and 14 years old number 34
million.
</P>
<P>
Haryono said the government's plan to increase cooperation with
the National Foster parents Movement (GNOTA) to make the nine-year
compulsory school program a success.
</P>
<P>
He said more than 1.7 million poor families will receive aid
from the GNOTA this year to send their children to school.
</P>
<P>
The program will cost between 130 billion rupiah (16.25 million
U.S. dollars) and 200 billion rupiah (25 million U.S. dollars), he
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
