<DATE_TIME> 1998-04-25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNICEF Supports Panama's New Law on Juvenile Delinquency </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PANAMA CITY, April 24 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
International Children's Fund (UNICEF) has backed a new draft law
on juvenile delinquency proposed by the Panamanian government,
UNICEF's Panama representative, Miguel Cuellar, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
"With the law proposed by the recently created government
commission to penalize juvenile delinquency and UNICEF
counselling, children will cease to be objects of the law to
become subjects of the law," Cuellar told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
He said the new law would help guarantee the rights of minors to
life, education, development and protection.
</P>
<P>
"The contribution of this new Panamanian legislation will
result in a change of outlook on unprotected, defenseless
children, subject to charity, and guarantee the compliance of
their rights on the part of the Panamanian state," said Cuellar.
</P>
<P>
He said that society and the government must create new ethics
that take into account the International Convention on
Children's Rights, ratified by Panama in 1990.
</P>
<P>
The UNICEF official noted that most crimes in Panama were
committed by adults while juvenile delinquency only accounted for
five percent.
</P>
<P>
"Behind those cases of juvenile delinquency there are
disintegrated households and poverty, where their right to
protection and to education has been denied to them," he said.
</P>
<P>
According to UNICEF statistics, approximately 50,000 children
and teenagers are made to work in Panama. The organization
estimates that 80 percent of children aged 10 to 14 drop out of
school to work.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF is carrying out a program known as "Casa Esperanza" to
provide education and work training for street children to help
their social integration.
</P>
<P>
Cuellar said that UNICEF also was also striving to combat infant
desertion through a program called "School Friends of Children"
that produced good results in Chile. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
